 ('148', '235', 'en_us', 'The Rainmaking Sessions - What\'s the matter with payments?', '<p>Startupbootcamp FinTech’s 2015 Trend Report highlighted a decrease in the volume of quality startups in the payments space. However, around 60% of UK respondents to a PwC Global FinTech survey think consumer banking and payments are going to be the most disrupted sectors over the next five years. Payments used to define what the industry thought of as FinTech disruption. However, new entrants to the market may have underestimated the relative complexity of payments. Will we see a new payments era emerge that is stronger, more mature and, at last, truly disruptive?<em>What’s the matter with payments?</em> will be an interactive, think tank style roundtable where you can hear from industry experts to debate and discuss the current state of the industry as well as future trends with your peers.</p><p>You will hear from:</p>\n\n<ul><li>Jon Prideaux, CEO at Boku</li><li>Richard Jackson, UK Managing Director, WoraPay</li><li>Moderation – Liz Lumley</li></ul><p>Please join us at the Rainmaking Loft to be a part of the Summer Season series of thought provoking Rainmaking Sessions looking at innovation and disruptive trends.</p><p>When: 16 June 2016\n\nWhere: The Rainmaking Loft, 1 St Katherine’s Way, London E1W 1UN\n\n\n\nAgenda</p>\n\n<ul><li>8:15 - Arrival at loft for coffee</li><li>8:30 – Buffet style breakfast served</li><li>8:45 - Welcome and talks begin</li><li>9:15 - Moderated Roundtable starts</li><li>10:30 - Breakfast Roundtable ends</li></ul><p>Spaces are limited, so please register now for your chance to be a part of this special event. Once you reserve your place, please shout about your attendance by sharing ‘I will be adding my views and insights to the #RainmakingSessions on <em>What’s the matter with payments?</em>on 16 June 2016!’ on your social media channels.</p><p>The Rainmaking Sessions – the Summer Season.</p><p><em>The Rainmaking Sessions</em><em> are series of monthly, breakfast roundtables to foster debate, discussion and discourse on the nature of innovation in corporates, FinTech, InsurTech, Digital Health and Smart Transportation.</em><em>To launch this exclusive, members-only think tank in the heart of London’s innovation community, three monthly events are planned to liven up the summer season.</em><em>Attendees will be signed up to a mailing list for information on future Rainmaking Sessions at the Rainmaking Loft. Please indicate if you do not want to be part of this mailing list. </em></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '[]', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/the-rainmaking-sessions-whats-the-matter-with-payments-tickets-25602215917', 'Rainmaking Loft - London', '1 St. Katherine\'s Way, London, E1W 1UN', '2016-06-16 07:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-10-27 08:29:57', '2016-11-15 18:07:37', 'e9e74d42-6898-45b1-9e56-e13ad90aa0a2'),
 ('149', '236', 'en_us', 'Shaping the FinTech future for banks and SMEs', '<p>According to data from the British Bankers Association (BBA) net lending to small to medium sized businesses in the UK reached of £2.1billion in the last quarter of 2015. Nevertheless, many banks are feeling the pressure from alternative finance and peer-to-peer lenders to meet the growing needs of what some estimate make up around 99% of the UK’s private sector businesses.</p><p>What strategies are banks using to ease the pace in which credit and loans are made available to these business? Will new alternative providers beat banks in the race for customers? Or will banks look to partner and collaborate with these new FinTech entrants to offer services better matched to the needs of a 21st Century business?</p><p><em>Shaping the FinTech future for banks and SMEs </em>will be an interactive, think tank style roundtable where you can hear from industry experts to debate and discuss the current state of the industry as well as future trends with your peers.</p><p>You will hear from:</p>\n\n<ul><li>Justin Hannemann, Head of Product Experience (Customer and Innovation), Santander UK</li><li>Johanna Pugh, global head of Lending, Misys</li><li>Moderation – Liz Lumley</li></ul><p>Please join us at the Rainmaking Loft to be a part of this series of thought provoking Rainmaking Sessions, sponsored by Misys, looking at innovative and disruptive trends.</p><p>Once you reserve your place, please shout about your attendance by sharing ‘I will be adding my views and insights to the #RainmakingSessions on <em>Shaping the FinTech future for banks and SMEs </em>14 July<em> </em>2016!’ on your social media channels.</p><p><em>The Rainmaking Sessions</em><em> are series of monthly, breakfast roundtables to foster debate, discussion and discourse on the nature of innovation in corporates, FinTech, InsurTech, Digital Health and Smart Transportantion and Energy.</em></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '[]', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/shaping-the-fintech-future-for-banks-and-smes-registration-26034413632', 'Rainmaking Loft - London', '1 St. Katherine\'s Way, London, E1W 1UN', '2016-07-14 07:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-10-27 08:56:50', '2016-11-15 18:05:21', '783a0864-1ac9-4b32-b19e-32367a9dd8c3'),
 ('150', '237', 'en_us', 'Video: Who Are Rainmaking?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Rainmaking Innovation partner, Nektarios Liolios explains what we are all about here at Rainmaking and gives an inside look into some of the ways that we are approaching corporate innovation.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"video-container\"><iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/c9Y0Zlm1Puc\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\"></iframe></div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Read the full transcript below.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>Interview with Nektarios Liolios</h1>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>My name is Nektarios Liolios, I\'m one of the partners of Rainmaking Innovation.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>What we do a Rainmaking Innovation is we help corporates find ways to innovate, as simple as that.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>People joke about the Kodak moments but, there is a Kodak moment.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The frustration that we see is organizations who are so conservative they actually don\'t understand that if they don\'t move faster they\'re actually running a real risk of failing, of disappearing.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The biggest challenge corporates face with innovation is that they actually don\'t know&nbsp;what they\'re doing. They get very excited, they also feel a lot of pressure to do something and then they randomly do things.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>One of the trends that we see, is organizations recognizing that working with startups is one channel but building products startup style is another, so the trend is really focusing on closing that loop. That\'s one of the things we see, the other one is really diversification. So, looking at innovation, not a box ticking exercise, but it\'s something that has to have many different iterations and many different facets.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>On the positive side, we see organizations trying a variety of different things; setting up their own investment funds, working with accelerators, doing their own incubation initiatives, having very structured programs for themselves. But also, putting a lot of effort into internal innovation initiatives by educating people about change, by giving them the opportunity to see other ways of working by giving them the opportunity to collaborate with competitors.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The smart organizations recognize that they need to do multiple things at the same time and they need to allow themselves to fail. They also need to connect the internal and external innovation efforts. If you just take startup engagement for instance; startups come in different stages and they have different needs and also different benefits for the organization. So, you can be part of an accelerator to see very early stage startups, to get excited by the the spirit and the drive and the passion of entrepreneurs, but also just to see the very latest trends.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>When it comes to using real technology that has been built by startups then you have to look at something that is maybe a little bit more advanced, maybe a little bit more mature, but that engagement has to be different. Maybe it\'s more like a managed lab, maybe it\'s trying to find ways of incorporating the technology into the business. And this is something that often happens by exploring. By using something like a startup studio, something like a separate entity, separate organization, that is bringing people together with startup experience and putting them together with project people from the organization who know about the business.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The interesting thing in this new and evolving landscape is that organizations still sometimes cling on to the idea of “we have to do everything ourselves,” and the smarter organizations recognize that there\'s certain things that you cannot do as a bank, as an insurer, as a large corporate by yourself. Because you don\'t have the know how, you don\'t have the expertise; but also, when It comes to collaboration, which is really important in this space, you usually cannot easily collaborate, by yourself, with other parties. So, having a neutral organization, having somebody like a startupbootcamp who would come in the middle, who brings people around the table and gets them to openly share their challenges, share their problems and priorities, and get them to jointly engage with startups is something that we\'ve seen being very successful.</p>', '[\"shortForm\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-10-27 09:01:29', '2016-11-15 17:22:32', '5bdb1899-cfe3-4f7b-9cbe-a77c976cd1ff'),
