 ('155', '242', 'en_us', 'These 3 Trends Are Revolutionizing Mobility', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '<p>Car2go, Uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from A to B. That is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant. Indeed&nbsp;<a href=\"https://files.lsecities.net/files/2015/09/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\">73% of households</a>&nbsp;in Berlin still own at least one car. Needless to say, if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable, we still have a long way to go. There are, however, trends that are spurring on this shift. We’ll take a closer look at three of them: smartphone adoption, urbanization, and “access over ownership”.<span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Germany, the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise. According to <a href=\"http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Germany-Posts-Big-Increase-Mobile-Internet-Use/1011884#sthash.vNbOGCYz.dpuf\">data&nbsp;from emarketer</a>, in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the Internet in comparison to 40% in 2013. In addition,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://files.lsecities.net/files/2015/09/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\">28% of Berlin residents</a>&nbsp;use travel apps with their smartphones daily, while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week. The further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology.<br></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>Urbanization</h1>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Urbanization is a global megatrend.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/gm.html\">Over 75% of the population</a>&nbsp;of Germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.cinum.org/en/urbanisation-mobility/88-90-114.html\">60% of the world’s population</a>&nbsp;will live in cities. Combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit, and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities. Due to this charging urban environment, car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support. The risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren’t open to, and supportive of, mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to. In addition to changes in public policy, we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life. This topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h1>“Access over Ownership”</h1>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.ted.com/talks/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman</a>, people are “wired to share.” In her book&nbsp;What’s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.emarketer.com/Article/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership/1012429\">report by Price Waterhouse Coopers</a>&nbsp;supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose “access over ownership”.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends – smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership – will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\"http://techcrunch.com/2015/11/17/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars/\">George Arison wrote</a>: “And anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.” Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn’t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we’ll be watching the latest developments very closely.</p>', '[\"longForm\"]', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-10-27 10:20:30', '2016-11-15 17:14:51', '8da9fb7b-af69-45ac-9a4e-bed40e18d1c6'),
 ('156', '243', 'en_us', 'The Rainmaking Sessions - Playing in the sandbox', '<p>Playing in the sandbox - <em>Can co-creation, between startups and incumbents, be the key to building successful products?</em></p><p>This year the Financial Conduct Authority launched the Regulatory Sandbox, which is meant to be a ‘safe space’ where businesses can test innovative products, services, business models and delivery mechanisms. This is a progressive step for startups in regulated industries, like financial services. However, many young companies still need active partnerships with established banks, firms and other corporates in order to test developing products with live data, enterprise architecture and an active customer base.Sandboxes, like the one set up by the FCA in the UK, are a step in the right direction for regulated industries. But they struggle to be useful if certain startups aren’t given the resources to test their products, properly. </p><p>What incentives can you give traditional firms to invite them into the sandbox to support startups to co-create industry-changing products? What procedures can you put in place to make sure co-creation is not only beneficial to startups, incumbents firms but to the regulatory process itself?</p><p><em>Playing in the sandbox, </em>will be an interactive, think tank style roundtable where you can hear from industry experts to debate and discuss the current state of the industry as well as future trends with your peers.</p><p>Please join us at the Rainmaking Loft to be a part of this series of thought provoking Rainmaking Sessions, trends that are shaping our industry.</p><p>You will hear from: </p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>Anna Wallace, Manager, Innovation Hub at the Financial Conduct Authority\n\n\n\n\n</li><li>Jon Pearson, London Lab Manager, Deutsche Bank LabsAgenda:</li></ul><ul><li>8:15 - Arrival at loft for coffee\n\n</li><li>8:30 – Buffet style breakfast served\n\n</li><li>8:45 - Welcome and talks begin\n\n</li><li>9:15 - Moderated Roundtable starts\n\n</li><li>10:30 - Breakfast Roundtable ends</li></ul><p>Spaces are limited, so please register with EventBrite for your chance to be a part of this special event.</p><p>Once you reserve your place, please shout about your attendance by sharing ‘I will be adding my views and insights to the #RainmakingSessions on <em>Playing in the sandbox on 11 </em>October!’ on your social media channels.The Rainmaking Sessions<em>The Rainmaking Sessions</em><em> are series of monthly, breakfast roundtables to foster debate, discussion and discourse on the nature of innovation in corporates, FinTech, InsurTech, Digital Health and Smart Transportation.</em></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '[]', NULL, NULL, 'https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/playing-in-the-sandbox-tickets-27541673888', 'Rainmaking Loft - London', '1 St. Katherine\'s Way, London, E1W 1UN', '2016-10-11 07:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-10-27 10:36:52', '2016-11-15 18:04:02', '1a4065bf-ada4-485e-b26a-1a2473f70530'),
