 ('50', '129', '4', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Sourcing Europe\'s Best EdTech Startups for Collaboration With Sanoma\",\"slug\":\"sourcing-europes-best-edtech-startups-for-collaboration-with-sanoma\",\"postDate\":1477412505,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"127\"],\"47\":{\"new3\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"For this project we were entrusted with finding hopeful EdTech startups with the potential to grow their business together with Sanoma, the Nordic region\\u2019s leading media and learning company.\\r\\n\\r\\nPromising startups were invited to participate in the \\u201cSanoma Startup Challenge - the future of learning\\u201d, an event which we designed and delivered to discover promising startup talent.\",\"image\":[\"122\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"The future of learning\",\"text\":\"Sanoma Ventures came to us looking for ways to find high quality deal flow for their newly formed corporate venture fund. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe media and education space has been making a steady shift away from traditional print and television to new models of delivery and distribution. Seeing the trend, Sanoma sought to partner and invest in startups that could provide different ways to reach students, distribute information and produce content.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"5 converge to compete in Amsterdam\",\"text\":\"Using our existing networks through our Startupbootcamp programs and dedicated research team we began surveying Europe for startups that could supply innovative shifts in Sanoma\\u2019s  business model.\\r\\n\\r\\nOur efforts spanned 22 European countries. We evaluated over 500 startups, encouraging over 100 high quality applications. From these, we hand-picked the best 50 to participate in the challenge.\\r\\nThe top 5 teams won an all-expenses paid trip to Amsterdam for the competition Final.\\r\\n\",\"image\":[\"123\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"new6\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"Our efforts spanned 22 European countries. We evaluated over 500 startups, encouraging over 100 high quality applications. From these, we hand-picked the best 50 to participate in the challenge.\\\"\",\"image\":[\"123\"]}},\"new7\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"The two-day competition offered startups the chance to work with mentors, Sanoma executives, Sanoma Learning industry experts and SanomaVenture\\u2019s investment team. \\r\\n\\r\\nBy exposing startups to these potential partners and customers, we pushed them to evolve their ideas, while demonstrating the potential benefits of collaboration between corporations and startups.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"new8\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Offering startups a wealth of opportunities\",\"text\":\"As a part of the Sanoma Startup Challenge, the startups were given the opportunity to make their final pitch at THENEXTWEB conference in Amsterdam, live on stage in front of Sanoma executives, investors and the full conference crowd.\\r\\n\\r\\nUltimately, a Danish startup, Labster, which offers next generation laboratory simulations, was named the winner, receiving a cash prize of \\u20ac25,000.\\r\\n\\r\\nSanoma continued to make investments in 18 ed-tech startups before closing the fund.\\r\\n\",\"image\":[\"124\"],\"align\":\"right\"}}},\"72\":[\"124\"],\"67\":\"\",\"69\":\"\",\"68\":\"\",\"71\":\"\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:21:46', '2016-10-25 16:21:46', '8a64a3e7-9e09-45d4-ad8d-28bb13b7d37c'),
 ('51', '136', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"What Do You Want Your Bank To Solve?\",\"slug\":\"what-do-you-want-your-bank-to-solve\",\"postDate\":1477412515,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"128\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>A couple of years ago, I attended a Bank Innovation afternoon, run by the lovely JP Nichols, where I encountered my first \\u2018persona\\u2019 exercise. The room was full of design people, FinTech folks and bankers. My group were the bankers.<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>We were assigned to create a person. A real-life person, with wants and desires, flaws and problems\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aand then create a banking relationship for that \\u2018person\\u2019. I was amazed by the variety of different people created by each group.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A group of designers created an old age pensioner, who lived in a rural community and was a widower. Some consultants outlined a single mother of two, who lived in the Northeast in the UK, and was going back to school to continue her education. Yet another group constructed a former addict in London, who had served in Iraq.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My group, the bankers? This was our guy:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li>A man (I think we ended up calling him Trevor)<\\/li><li> 28 years old. University and above education.<\\/li><li>Works for a large corporate, but wants to start his own business eventually.<\\/li><li>Small pension plan established.<\\/li><li>Owns his own home&nbsp;&hellip; in <i>London.<\\/i> &lt;==WTF?<\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I had to stop them. (They were all getting collective hard-ons about the type of small business loans their bank would sell to this future Steve Jobs of the UK.) I had to ask\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a\\u2018<i>Does this perfect human being have any flaws? Any problems?\\u2019<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>They stared at me blankly.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u2018<i>Ok, guys\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ais he married, does he have a girlfriend<\\/i>?\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>No, girlfriend as of yet\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abut definitely wants to get married some day<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I wrote\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a\\u2018<i>Uses Tinder\\u2019<\\/i> on a Post-It<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Really, online dating? Would our guy do that?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u2018<i>YES!<\\/i>\\u2019 I screamed. (The room got a bit quiet then) \\u2018<i>Your perfect, 28 year old Oxbridge grad, with an endless disposable income\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agiven that he has a pension AND owns his own home in London\\u200a&mdash;\\u200acannot actually magic up the perfect trophy wife at will. He uses Tinder just like all the rest of you<\\/i>.\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The group started discussing what type of cool, hip tech startup this guy would start before his 30th birthday.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u2018<i>Gentlemen!<\\/i> (I can get loud when I\\u2019m not being heard&nbsp;;-) ) <i>Focus\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abefore you start selling \\u2018Trevor\\u2019 a wide range of banking products, we have to discuss his flaws, his quirks\\u200a&mdash;\\u200athe stuff that makes him a real human being. Does he have a gambling problem, for example?\\u2019<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>At that point one of the men in the group took my pink Post-It pad and Sharpie and wrote \\u2018Buys scratch cards\\u2019 on a sheet and triumphantly stuck it on the flip board.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Why am I telling you this story?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This week I was asked to think about some stories that addressed customer facing problems that banks can try and solve. My brain went into action. Account opening! KYC! Identity!<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I was no different from those \\u2018bankers\\u2019 two years ago. I started thinking about bank products\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agranted I was thinking about how these bank products aren\\u2019t fit for many individual people\\u2019s purposes\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abut I was being product-centric nevertheless.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I decided to walk through my life.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li>I want a way that I can get from my house in the morning to my desk in my office in the cheapest and most efficient way possible. &lt;==<i>Southeastern Rail is not delivering<\\/i><\\/li><li><i><\\/i>&nbsp;I want to be able to get a taxi anytime and anywhere, without going to an ATM first &lt;==<i>Oh ya, Uber solved that<\\/i><\\/li><li><i><\\/i>I want to be able to walk around a conference centre, in my dress with no pockets, and still hold onto\\u200a&mdash;\\u200amy bank card, my phone, a lipstick and a tampon\\u200a&mdash;\\u200awithout carrying a huge bag &lt;==<i>My \\u2018tiny, pretty, purse\\u2019 startup company is looking for funds now<\\/i><\\/li><li><i><\\/i>I want a summer house at the bottom of my garden.<\\/li><li>I want my son to have guitar lessons<\\/li><li>I want to know I can buy a ticket to the US at a moment notice if my family needs me<\\/li><li>I want to be able to work at something until I have more grey hair than I have now<\\/li><li>I want my son to go to university where the only thing he has to worry about is studying and having enough weekly beer money\\u200a&mdash;\\u200alike I did.<\\/li><\\/ul><p>Can a bank look at all of that and think\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aWhat are the services we have now that can help you achieve some of that and if not, what can we develop that can?<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Or would they try and sell me a \\u2018loan\\u2019?<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:21:55', '2016-10-25 16:21:55', '7a587b2d-daa2-4412-acaf-4d5b80d19aa2'),
 ('52', '139', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Women Are More Fun :)\",\"slug\":\"women-are-more-fun\",\"postDate\":1477412700,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"137\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Women are more fun\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agame over&nbsp;:-)<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>After almost 22 years in this financial technology business, I have been to my fair share of events and dinners and meetups. I have sat through an hour long lecture on the problems inherent in the Payments Services Directive in Luxembourg. I\\u2019ve seen people slam their fists on a table in protest to the idea that social sign-in for bank accounts could be workable. I once belonged to the MiFID working group.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>But I have never ended an evening of discussion and chat in the FinTech space where several people left with comments such as:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u201cThis was the best meetup I have ever been too.\\u201d and (my favourite) \\u201cThis was better than the party I went to on Saturday night.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This was last night and the occasion was the second FemTech meetup, run by the formidable Ghela Boscovich of Zafin Labs and hosted by Lloyds Banking Group. The FemTech meetups were born out of a Swift Innotribe project for Sibos last year, and enabled by Sam Maule of Carlisle Consulting, to showcase and promote the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.femtechleaders.com\\/\\\">various women who work in global financial technology.<\\/a><\\/p><p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.femtechleaders.com\\/\\\"><\\/a>The numbers are appalling. <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cityam.com\\/236156\\/women-in-fintech-four-ways-to-close-the-gender-gap-\\\">Less than five percent of startup founders<\\/a> in the FinTech space are women. Financial News published their annual <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.efinancialnews.com\\/gallery\\/financial-news-women-finance-survey\\\">Women in Finance <\\/a>survey\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aand the results show a mostly discouraged and, almost, depressed female workforce.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What tends to get me angry (and I am trying not to write blogs angry anymore\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ahowever, passion is my muse!) is that whenever anyone in this industry talks about diversity, the burden of proof tends to fall on the people advocating diversity rather than those who sit idly by accepting the status quo.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When just advocating the need for more women (just women, mind you!\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a50 percent of the population!) to participate in the FinTech space, statistics need to be rolled out highlighting how female led business tend to be more profitable or showing that adding women to their boards adds to a company\\u2019s longevity. Debates around systematic basis within financial services and tech, the glass ceiling and whether or not women know how to adequately \\u2018lean in\\u2019 (or whether they even need to) are starting to grate on my last nerve.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>So, in an effort to cultivate this attitude of focusing in the positive, I am going to throw out a brand new, entirely unscientific theory about why there needs to be more women in the FinTech space and why your company needs to hire more women now.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Women are more fun.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>There, I said it. Women make work more pleasant. They laugh, they are supportive. I don\\u2019t know many women who would sit and lecture for an hour on the PSD, in a stuffy room, in a grey suit. But I know many who would chat about the ramifications of the PSD 2, while wearing statement jewellery and sipping a glass of wine. Which room would you rather sit in?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>There it is\\u200a&mdash;\\u200amy positive vibes for this week. Women make work and life and Tuesday night meetups talking about digital banking with Lloyds\\u2019 John Webster\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aa lot more fun. Pass me a glass of wine.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/0ckJlJdo2-DFSJPuF.jpeg#asset:138:url\\\" alt=\\\"0ckJlJdo2-DFSJPuF.jpeg#asset:138\\\"><br><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:26:21', '2016-10-25 16:26:21', '9ffdc92d-215c-40f7-b2a5-3920b4328eb7'),
 ('53', '142', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"The Key To Fostering Corporate Innovation Culture? Inside Out!\",\"slug\":\"the-key-to-fostering-corporate-innovation-culture-inside-out\",\"postDate\":1477413086,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"141\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Many large firms are currently grappling with ways to incorporate a more innovative culture into their development and organisational environments. As with any large transformational project, success or failure tend to depend on the right mix of culture and human relationships.<\\/p><figure><img src=\\\"https:\\/\\/cdn-images-2.medium.com\\/max\\/600\\/1*R4W0ngz83mfRFgwBjTER3g.png\\\"><\\/figure>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><br><\\/p><p>This was the main crux of the discussion at the inaugural Rainmaking Session\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aHow to foster a corporate innovation culture\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ahosted by Rainmaking Innovation in May.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A wide range of corporate innovation leaders and learners from organisations as diverse as Standard & Poors, BP and SwissRe gathered to hear a discussion led by Rachael Jackson, Solutions, Design, Services at RBS and Alex Farcet, partner at Rainmaking Innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The conversation around the table, conducted under the Chatham House Rule, came thick and fast as participants relayed stories of their own companies\\u2019 internal challenges, strategies and successes. The only interruption to the discussion came when two enormous anti-terrorist transformer helicopters buzzed the Rainmaking Loft!<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The main findings from the roundtable were as follows:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation leaders at corporations need to operate with one leg inside an organisation and one leg outside. Being outside a firm allows the leaders to learn and discover new technologies and new business models that can transform the enterprise. While keeping a foot inside a company, keeps lines of communication and collaboration open with senior people at the firm.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This line of talk moved onto a debate on whether innovation departments need to be centralised, and separate from the main organisation, with their own staff, budget and authority or decentralised. The centralised model had the advantages of a separate budget line which would allow projects to develop without relying on the P&L of separate business units. The decentralised approach emphasised the importance of encouraging the entire firm to engage in innovation projects and activities.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation tends to signal change for most companies and change is scary. People and culture are key to ensuring that establishing and innovation culture is seen as beneficial and empowering to the rest of the organisation.<\\/p><p><br><\\/p><p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/1KuyS3TbSOtuUIL3loV17JA.png#asset:140\\\"><br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Many around the Rainmaking Session breakfast table recognised that many innovation projects were led by either senior management or staff working hands on in development. It was the so-called \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 that was most in need of empowerment when it came to innovation. Many argued that this \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 was not incentivised to try anything new or to embark on innovation projects that have the possibility of failure embedded in its DNA.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation projects are hard to measure, and including metrics at all might be detrimental to its successes. However, most large corporates operate in a risk culture that requires performance metrics and measurement. The \\u2018can\\u2019t live with metrics\\/can\\u2019t live without metrics\\u2019 debate continues.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Finally, the roundtable debate focused engaging with and working with startups. The large corporate around the table all expressed an interest and a desire to work with startups\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agiven that the search for new technologies and solutions is often found in the startup community.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their advice for any startup looking to sell into or partner with a larger organisation was to make sure that they presented their value proposition in a way that made sense for the corporate and their clients\\u2019 needs. If that value proposition was met correctly, a partnership between a corporate and a startup would be more likely to be successful. These successful projects could then be used as evidence to the rest of the company that embarking on an innovation culture was beneficial and worthwhile.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><i>Please join us, or invite a colleague, for our next Rainmaking Session on June 16th\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aWhat\\u2019s the matter with payments?<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><i>You will hear from:<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u00b7 <i>Jon Prideaux, CEO at Boku<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u00b7 <i>Richard Jackson, UK Managing Director, WoraPay<\\/i><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.eventbrite.co.uk\\/e\\/the-rainmaking-sessions-whats-the-matter-with-payments-tickets-25602215917\\\"><i><\\/i><\\/a><i><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.eventbrite.co.uk\\/e\\/the-rainmaking-sessions-whats-the-matter-with-payments-tickets-25602215917\\\">https:\\/\\/www.eventbrite.co.uk\\/e...<\\/a><\\/i><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:31:26', '2016-10-25 16:31:26', '4191ebc4-c72c-4637-be8d-3b2ce6eb2936'),
 ('54', '144', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Shaping the Future of Banks and SMEs\",\"slug\":\"shaping-the-future-of-banks-and-smes\",\"postDate\":1477413260,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"143\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Peers from a wide range of UK and European banks, along with a couple of FinTech startups, arrived at the Rainmaking Loft for the last in the Summer Season for the Rainmaking Sessions. As the group munched on bacon rolls and sipped tea and coffee, all were in the room with the understanding that small to medium sized businesses are a group that is under loved, underserved and ripe with opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The roundtable discussion, led by Justin Hannemann, Head of Product Experience (Customer and Innovation), Santander UK and Johanna Pugh, global head of Lending, Misys caused several themes to emerge from the table.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>SMEs are quite diverse and can range from everything from a tech-savvy FinTech startup in London to a cat grooming store in Sheffield, for example. This makes SMEs hard to classify and are seen as risky and complex by banks. Categorisation is hard when <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/blog.thecompanywarehouse.co.uk\\/2012\\/07\\/31\\/what-is-an-sme\\/\\\">definitions differ<\\/a> between UK government departments, HMRC and even the EU. As banks enhance their services to retail customers and larger commercial organisations, SMEs get pushed to the bottom.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Internal bank politics as well as legacy systems don\\u2019t make it easier for traditional firms to develop services that meets the needs of most SMEs. Many banks make due with an enhanced retail bank offering or a \\u2018lite\\u2019 version of their corporate offerings\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aboth versions tend to fall short of meeting SME needs. Legacy systems inside banks can also make it difficult to shift customer accounts from one product set to another if an SME is initially put in the \\u2018retail portfolio\\u2019 at the bank.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Despite much discussion around open APIs and working with FinTech startups, many banks around the table favoured a more human approach to better meet SME needs. Bringing customers into the bank, even giving some of them a seat on the board, was seen as the main tool to better understand SME needs and break down internal barriers at the bank. \\u201cThey are the boss,\\u201d was one comment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>SME pain points can be huge. They are working 24\\/7 to keep their business running, but many lack basic accounting skills or are uneasy about chasing unpaid invoices. SMEs are looking for control and simplification, according to the roundtable. SMEs want to be able to make deposits, get invoices paid and not have to deal with complex or confusing financial products.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Digital did not reign supreme with SME needs either. Many SMEs are looking for access to human-led customer service where they could pick up the phone and speak to an expert at any time. \\u201cWhen you are dealing with amounts over six figures, people want a personal chat, not 100% digital\\u201d, was one roundtable comment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Globally, the majority of businesses can be classified as small businesses. The future of SMEs is central to the future of FinTech and corporate banking. Empowering SMEs and helping them shape their future is a huge opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To find out more about Rainmaking Innovation follow us on @rainmakinginnov or visit us at <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/rainmaking.io\\/\\\">https:\\/\\/rainmaking.io\\/<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To find out more about Misys visit <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.misys.com\\/solutions\\/fusionbanking\\/lending\\/\\\">http:\\/\\/www.misys.com\\/solutions\\/fusionbanking\\/lending\\/<\\/a><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:34:20', '2016-10-25 16:34:20', 'f7d94cd2-9f99-42b7-8615-23e76cc55a61'),
 ('55', '146', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Missed Connections in the Sandbox\",\"slug\":\"missed-connections-in-the-sandbox\",\"postDate\":1477413388,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"145\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>This week, industry thought leaders from incumbent banks and FinTech startups gathered in the Rainmaking Loft for the first in the Autumn Season for the Rainmaking Sessions\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a<i>Playing in the sandbox<\\/i>. The session looked at the establishment of the Regulatory Sandbox run by the Financial Conduct Authority and the appetite and capability of many incumbent banks to participate in the new scheme and partner with new entrants to the financial services landscape.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The outcome? There are many footprints in the sandbox, but many may have to wait some time for impressive castles to be built.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA\\u2019s Regulatory Sandbox is meant to be a legal framework or a \\u2018safe space\\u2019 where businesses can test innovative products, services, business models and delivery mechanisms. This is a progressive step for startups in regulated industries, like financial services. However, many young companies still need active partnerships with established banks, firms and other corporates in order to test developing products with live data, enterprise architecture and an active customer base.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Sandboxes, like the one set up by the FCA in the UK, are a step in the right direction for regulated industries. But they struggle to be useful if certain startups aren\\u2019t given the resources to test their products, properly.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA sandbox was designed to allow for collaboration. Currently, there are many FinTech startups involved in the programme. The FCA does not make public the names or the number of startups participating in the sandbox. However, many of these companies still require participation from incumbent banks in order to adequately test their offerings in the safe legal framework the FCA has established.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>However many banks, themselves, are working on creating their own innovation labs to not only support and welcome new technology and services entrants, but to enable and empower their own internal staff to embrace innovation. Many in this industry know that incumbent banks and financial services firms move at a pace considered much slower than is enjoyed in the Silicon Valley-style startup world. This is true even for banks that are working towards creating a more agile and flexible work environment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The window of opportunity is open now to work within the FCA Regulatory Sandbox. This time around the pace of change and collaboration may be more \\u2018missed connections\\u2019 than Match.com.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:36:28', '2016-10-25 16:36:28', '4d7d672e-9c96-4540-a8ff-d6938c6d7369'),
 ('56', '149', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"The Future of Customer Acquisition is Already Here\",\"slug\":\"the-future-of-customer-acquisition-is-already-here\",\"postDate\":1477414085,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"148\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Chatbots are more than just the latest marketing gimmick \\u2013 they\\u2019re a clue to how the internet itself is likely to evolve. Insurers without a plan for some form of chatbot pilot risk losing out as online advertising undergoes its next big step change.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Chatbots are the hottest customer-centric innovative technology of 2016 so far. In March,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/2016\\/3\\/30\\/11332494\\/microsoft-bot-framework-build\\\">Microsoft<\\/a>&nbsp;announced the launch of a new platform that will enable anyone to build one. In April,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2016\\/04\\/12\\/agents-on-messenger\\/\\\">Facebook<\\/a>&nbsp;announced the launch of chatbots on its existing Messenger platform.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What are chatbots? At the most basic level, these are computer programs that use artificial intelligence to simulate conversations with a real person.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>They have the obvious potential benefit of replacing customer service staff \\u2013 or freeing up those employees for other tasks, thus increasing productivity. But the marketing potential is even greater, as they enable companies to initiate conversations with customers online based on what sites they\\u2019re on and what kind of services they might be looking for.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><b>Targeting new customers more effectively<\\/b>\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In insurance, they could be used to replace the need to fill out long, tedious forms. Not only that, but since a chatbot can initiate a conversation, you can use them to proactively target prospective customers rather than wait for them to come to you. This is the vision behind Spixii, a startup we\\u2019ve been working with at InsurTech.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Spixii aims to make the buying of health and travel insurance more intuitive and fun for millennials, and to generate more revenues for insurers by opening up the relatively untapped millennial market \\u2013 and then upselling to these consumers in a more targeted and less pushy manner.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>With Spixii, the chatbot acts you\\u2019re having an online conversation with a human insurance agent, asking you questions and responding to your answers. The consumer gets a more engaging experience than just filling out a form, while the insurer can carry out an accurate risk assessment.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Right now Spixii has several tier one insurers interested in partnering with them to run a pilot. They also have just been accepted on the Allianz Accelerator programme in France to test their offering further. Cynics may dismiss the technology as a gimmick. But no one can afford not to start experimenting with it, for one very simple reason: Facebook wants to supplant Google as the number one advertising platform on the internet, and they\\u2019re investing heavily in chatbots to help them do this.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><b>Facebook is no longer a social media company \\u2013 here\\u2019s why that matters<\\/b>\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.vox.com\\/2016\\/5\\/10\\/11640140\\/facebook-media-influence\\\">Facebook<\\/a>&nbsp;is no longer a social network. It\\u2019s a technology holding company just like Google, and it now comprises social media, photo-sharing (Instagram), messaging (WhatsApp) and virtual reality (Oculus). It\\u2019s also the largest media distributor in history.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The company has grown with one goal: to make it so that no one who uses the internet ever has to leave the Facebook platform. Once we reach \\u201cPeak Facebook\\u201d \\u2013 the point at which the majority of the world\\u2019s internet users spend all their internet time on one or other of Facebook\\u2019s apps \\u2013 it will become pointless to advertise anywhere else.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>After all, Facebook already tales up 22% of the internet time that Americans spend on mobile devices, compared with 11% on Google search and YouTube combined. And Facebook\'s advertising revenues have more than doubled in the last two years, to <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.economist.com\\/news\\/briefing\\/21696507-social-network-has-turned-itself-one-worlds-most-influential-technology-giants\\\">$18 billion in 2015<\\/a>.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><b>Chatbot failure is not an option<\\/b>\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>And why is Facebook so interested in chatbots? Because by creating its own advertising platform, it can control how people buy products and services online. Specifically, the company wants the whole transaction to take place within its own platform \\u2013 so customers never have to leave it. And hosting chatbots looks set to be one of the most effective ways of doing this.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Now, this trend towards internet dominance may or may not pay off. And it certainly throws up some questions about the fact that Facebook could end up with complete control \\u2013 or at least de facto dominance \\u2013 over how companies can advertise to their consumers online. But Facebook\\u2019s growth has been so phenomenal, and its increasing influence so unstoppable, that running some kind of chatbot pilot is not something insurers can afford to see as a luxury. It\\u2019s a necessity.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><b>How insurers can exploit this trend<\\/b>\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The fastest way to trial your own chatbot is through partnerships and pilots \\u2013 either with technology companies themselves or with innovative startups who aim to solve a business problem that you\\u2019re struggling with.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To go back to the example of Spixii I mentioned before: this company represents an ideal opportunity for insurers to tap into the millennial market, and, in so doing, to investigate how the technology could be extended to reach other markets and develop attractive new propositions and products. Plus, it potentially offers a level of customer engagement and insight for small premium insurance products that just wouldn\\u2019t be affordable otherwise.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Facebook is serious about this technology. If successful, it could transform the world of online advertising beyond recognition. It may be that insurers can\\u2019t afford not to trial the technology, but those who are successful stand to reap huge potential rewards.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\"}}', '2016-10-25 16:48:05', '2016-10-25 16:48:05', 'ca8a76f1-bfbf-4012-a0c0-d9c7f071bd90'),
 ('57', '158', '4', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Startup MENA: Empowering Entrepreneurs in the Middle East and North Africa\",\"slug\":\"startup-mena-empowering-entrepreneurs-in-the-middle-east-and-north-africa\",\"postDate\":1477415700,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"156\"],\"47\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"In 2014, we partnered with The Danish Foreign Ministry to deliver a 2 year program stimulating economic growth, creating businesses and jobs in the private sectors in Egypt, Jordan and Tunisia. \",\"image\":[\"147\"]}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Seeding a Startup Ecosystem\",\"text\":\"Since 2003 The Danish government has been actively collaborating with the Middle East and North Africa to strengthen their dialogue, understanding and cooperation, and to promote and support the ongoing reform and democratisation processes in the region.\\r\\n\\r\\nHowever, political revolution and unemployment still threaten to impede the successful democratisation process in some countries in the region. Stimulating job creation has therefore become a key objective for The Danish-Arab Partnership Program across the region. \",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"In 2014, high rates of unemployment continued, particularly amongst young people, despite many being well-educated, ready to work and keen to actively help shape the future of their countries. \\r\\n\\r\\nIt was in this context that we were challenged to design and deliver a program with The Danish Foreign Ministry: creating jobs and growth through entrepreneurship.\",\"image\":[\"151\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"new4\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Leading Through Value \",\"text\":\"As our team was new to the region, we knew that the existing ecosystem would measure us on the basis of the value we displayed. To ensure our event attendees left with new insights, knowledge, and inspiration, we brought expertise, high-profile international mentors, and investors to our events.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"new5\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"We designed and delivered a range of events to support and encourage local startups:\",\"text\":\"\\u2022 Two investment labs\\r\\n\\u2022 Two 48 hour hackathons\\r\\n\\u2022 Four women\\u2019s meetups\\r\\n\\u2022 Six mini bootcamps\\r\\n\\u2022 Three open offices\\r\\n\\u2022 Two job fairs\\r\\n\\u2022 Two investor pitch events\\r\\n\\u2022 One corporate matchmaking event\\r\\n\\u2022 A series of intensive, high impact workshops\\r\\n\",\"image\":[\"150\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"new6\":{\"type\":\"imageBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"images\":[\"152\",\"153\",\"154\",\"155\"]}},\"new7\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Over two years we hosted 27 events across Jordan, Egypt and Tunisia \",\"text\":\"+ 90 jobs created\\r\\n+ 820 entrepreneurs\\r\\n+ 70 partners\\r\\n+ 130 startups engaged\\r\\n+ 160 mentors engaged\\r\\n+ 10.000 in network\\r\\n\",\"backgroundColour\":\"white\"}}},\"72\":[\"147\"],\"67\":\"\",\"69\":\"\",\"68\":\"\",\"71\":\"\"}}', '2016-10-25 17:20:40', '2016-10-25 17:20:40', '13ae483b-e292-44bf-86d8-44a4eafcf556'),
