estment funds, working with accelerators, doing their own incubation initiatives, having very structured programs for themselves. But also, putting a lot of effort into internal innovation initiatives by educating people about change, by giving them the opportunity to see other ways of working by giving them the opportunity to collaborate with competitors.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The smart organizations recognize that they need to do multiple things at the same time and they need to allow themselves to fail. They also need to connect the internal and external innovation efforts. If you just take startup engagement for instance; startups come in different stages and they have different needs and also different benefits for the organization. So, you can be part of an accelerator to see very early stage startups, to get excited by the the spirit and the drive and the passion of entrepreneurs, but also just to see the very latest trends.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When it comes to using real technology that has been built by startups then you have to look at something that is maybe a little bit more advanced, maybe a little bit more mature, but that engagement has to be different. Maybe it\'s more like a managed lab, maybe it\'s trying to find ways of incorporating the technology into the business. And this is something that often happens by exploring. By using something like a startup studio, something like a separate entity, separate organization, that is bringing people together with startup experience and putting them together with project people from the organization who know about the business.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The interesting thing in this new and evolving landscape is that organizations still sometimes cling on to the idea of \\u201cwe have to do everything ourselves,\\u201d and the smarter organizations recognize that there\'s certain things that you cannot do as a bank, as an insurer, as a large corporate by yourself. Because you don\'t have the know how, you don\'t have the expertise; but also, when It comes to collaboration, which is really important in this space, you usually cannot easily collaborate, by yourself, with other parties. So, having a neutral organization, having somebody like a startupbootcamp who would come in the middle, who brings people around the table and gets them to openly share their challenges, share their problems and priorities, and get them to jointly engage with startups is something that we\'ve seen being very successful.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 09:29:28', '2016-10-27 09:29:28', '42b0df4c-b747-4bbd-aa69-10244005e1f2'),
 ('112', '237', '5', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Who Are Rainmaking?\",\"slug\":\"who-are-rainmaking\",\"postDate\":1477558860,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"218\"],\"17\":[\"shortForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Rainmaking Innovation partner, Nektarios Liolios explains what we are all about here at Rainmaking and gives an inside look into some of the ways that we are approaching corporate innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Check out the video <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=c9Y0Zlm1Puc\\\">here<\\/a> or read the full transcript below.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Video Transcript:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My name is Nektarios Liolios, I\'m one of the partners of Rainmaking Innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What we do a Rainmaking Innovation is we help corporates find ways to innovate, as simple as that.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>People joke about the Kodak moments but, there is a Kodak moment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The frustration that we see is organizations who are so conservative they actually don\'t understand that if they don\'t move faster they\'re actually running a real risk of failing, of disappearing.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The biggest challenge corporates face with innovation is that they actually don\'t know&nbsp;what they\'re doing. They get very excited, they also feel a lot of pressure to do something and then they randomly do things.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One of the trends that we see, is organizations recognizing that working with startups is one channel but building products startup style is another, so the trend is really focusing on closing that loop. That\'s one of the things we see, the other one is really diversification. So, looking at innovation, not a box ticking exercise, but it\'s something that has to have many different iterations and many different facets.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>On the positive side, we see organizations trying a variety of different things; setting up their own investment funds, working with accelerators, doing their own incubation initiatives, having very structured programs for themselves. But also, putting a lot of effort into internal innovation initiatives by educating people about change, by giving them the opportunity to see other ways of working by giving them the opportunity to collaborate with competitors.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The smart organizations recognize that they need to do multiple things at the same time and they need to allow themselves to fail. They also need to connect the internal and external innovation efforts. If you just take startup engagement for instance; startups come in different stages and they have different needs and also different benefits for the organization. So, you can be part of an accelerator to see very early stage startups, to get excited by the the spirit and the drive and the passion of entrepreneurs, but also just to see the very latest trends.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When it comes to using real technology that has been built by startups then you have to look at something that is maybe a little bit more advanced, maybe a little bit more mature, but that engagement has to be different. Maybe it\'s more like a managed lab, maybe it\'s trying to find ways of incorporating the technology into the business. And this is something that often happens by exploring. By using something like a startup studio, something like a separate entity, separate organization, that is bringing people together with startup experience and putting them together with project people from the organization who know about the business.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The interesting thing in this new and evolving landscape is that organizations still sometimes cling on to the idea of \\u201cwe have to do everything ourselves,\\u201d and the smarter organizations recognize that there\'s certain things that you cannot do as a bank, as an insurer, as a large corporate by yourself. Because you don\'t have the know how, you don\'t have the expertise; but also, when It comes to collaboration, which is really important in this space, you usually cannot easily collaborate, by yourself, with other parties. So, having a neutral organization, having somebody like a startupbootcamp who would come in the middle, who brings people around the table and gets them to openly share their challenges, share their problems and priorities, and get them to jointly engage with startups is something that we\'ve seen being very successful.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 09:29:59', '2016-10-27 09:29:59', '388f2c97-89b0-443d-ad8b-0792b932bdb5'),
