 ('115', '223', '5', '15', 'en_us', '5', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"What Banks Are Actually Doing To Innovate\",\"slug\":\"what-banks-are-actually-doing-to-innovate\",\"postDate\":1477489920,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"215\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":[\"211\"],\"15\":\"<p>You cannot read a finance publication for too long without reading the phrase \\u201cripe for disruption.\\u201d&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>By now the rhetoric is well understood, banks must innovate in order to maintain their market leading positions and gain the trust and business of the next generation. What you hear less of is what banks are actually doing to become more innovative.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>We took a look at four different banks and examples of the strategies that they are employing.&nbsp;<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/thumbnailimage.jpg#asset:217:url\\\" alt=\\\"thumbnailimage.jpg#asset:217\\\"><br><br>BNY&nbsp;Mellon<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>BNY Mellon understands the importance of fostering an innovation culture, challenging employees to adopt a flexible mindset that encourages new ways of thinking and an openness to doing things differently. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>BNY Mellon actively mines its employees for innovative ideas and seeks out exceptional talent internally. This focus on \\u2018intrapreneurship\\u2019 is seen through its annual internal innovation competition, A.C.E. This challenges employees to develop innovative ideas, rewarding winners with resources and funding to be incubated in one of the bank\\u2019s innovation centers, located in Palo Alto, Pittsburgh, London, New Jersey, Pune and Chennai. Innovation training further helps employees develop ideation skills, whilst a social collaboration platform allows employees to discuss new ideas they are working on and collaborate.&nbsp; \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>BNY Mellon\\u2019s focus on a cultural shift in mindset has begun to manifest itself in real technological innovation and competence. The bank\\u2019s IT departments have adopted agile development practices involving small teams that take a continuous delivery approach to development, rolling out frequent production updates and reducing delivery time. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Further encouraging an innovative culture, the IT department has increased its ability to collaborate by sharing resources and knowledge across the entire organization. The NEXEN Digital Ecosystem was developed by the bank as way to increase the speed of delivery and value to clients. NEXEN is an open sourced cloud based architecture that includes a methodology for developing API\\u2019s with one language and documentation. These API\\u2019s are available to the company\\u2019s developers and consumers through an API store where they can utilize the platform\\u2019s library to create new applications.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Previously, developers would create applications in their own language and with separate micro-code monitoring. Now they are able to quickly tie together applications via API and manage them in one cloud based management system. Because monitoring is built into the NEXEN system, all applications can be tracked and monitored in unison, allowing for greater data insights and more intelligent decision making.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This platform was made possible due to the Bank\\u2019s commitment to encouraging a mindset of innovation by directly addressing the breadth of change required at every level of the organization and getting strong sponsorship from executive levels.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1><br><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/bbva-open-talent-ganadores-europa-2016_0.jpg#asset:219:url\\\" alt=\\\"bbva-open-talent-ganadores-europa-2016_0\\\"><br><br>BBVA <\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>BBVA\\u2019s Strategy and Innovation unit was created in 2007, as part of the Technology and Operations department, whose key objective was to integrate emerging technologies into the banking industry, resulting in projects such as ABIL, the first smart ATM. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>BBVA has turned to open innovation models in order to overcome existing challenges and attract the best talent. BBVA has opened Innovation Centers, such as those in Madrid (Spain) and Bogota (Colombia), and focused on developing a knowledge network around these. This approach depends upon ecosystems for innovation and talent worldwide and seeks to foster a culture of collaboration with entrepreneurs, startups and developers.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The Innovation Centers generate ideas and accelerates these through a process of experimentation and prototyping. The value of this approach was demonstrated in 2008 when BBVA became one of the first banks in Europe to introduce online money management (PFM).\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The Innovation Centers form hubs, points from which to engage with the wider FinTech ecosystem. BBVA has established an innovation network comprised of partners, such as tech giants Google, IBM, Cisco and Microsoft, as well as academic institutions, like the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) and Stanford, commercial organizations, like Gartner and Continuum, and startups. This sharing of knowledge and ideas encourages cross-pollination and helps generate innovation for BBVA. &nbsp;\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In addition, BBVA hosts the Open Talent Challenge, now in its 8###sup\\/sup### cycle. This global startup competition focuses on attracting innovative startups that are transforming financial services, offering the winner a place on a two-week Immersion and Interaction program. &nbsp;\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Most recently, in February 2016 BBVA announced the closure of its in-house venture arm, BBVA Ventures. Instead, BBVA Venture\\u2019s portfolio, the $100 million allotted fund, and an additional $150 million, is being put into a new VC \\u2013 Propel Venture Partners - based in San Francisco and London. BBVA has become a limited partner in Propel and will focus on payments, credit, insurance, wealth management, e-commerce, and security & compliance. The move reflects BBVA\\u2019s belief that their increased capital, and Propel\\u2019s independence and London presence, will attract the best FinTech startups.&nbsp; \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/20151112_130526.jpg#asset:220:url\\\" alt=\\\"20151112_130526.jpg#asset:220\\\">&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Santander<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Santander engages in a wide range of complementary innovation activities. Most notably, Santander has launched Openbank, a fully digital bank, several Digital Labs, and InnoVentures, the bank\\u2019s venture capital arm with a FinTech focused fund of over $100 million.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>InnoVentures invests in FinTech startups that the fund believes can add value to the bank\\u2019s customers. This is wide ranging, covering everything from payments, alternative lending and personal finance management. The fund also selects investments based on the value that the bank can bring to the startup by introducing customers, helping to establish a strong position within the FinTech ecosystem. In addition to acting as an investment vehicle, InnoVentures serves as a funnel for startups and new technologies into Santander\\u2019s other innovation initiatives. Even if InnoVentures does not invest in a startup there is the opportunity to partner with them to explore new technology or specific use cases, through running pilots or proof of concepts. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\\r\\n Openbank is another example of Santander\\u2019s multi layered approach. Serving the Spanish market, Openbank is a completely digital bank that operates under its own brand but is supported by Santander. As a completely digital bank, the venture offers a unique proposition to customers and is a standalone business. Openbank is not reliant on Santander\\u2019s central processes and legacy IT infrastructure creating additional value as an innovation initiative as startups\\u2019 technologies can be integrated much faster than with Santander itself.&nbsp;<br><br><br><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/Citibank_Chinatown.jpg#asset:222:url\\\" alt=\\\"Citibank_Chinatown.jpg#asset:222\\\"><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Citi<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Citi has developed a portfolio of initiatives; engaging both the external innovation ecosystem and creating internal initiatives to encourage new mindsets and ways of working.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Citi Ventures oversees a global network of labs and, in 2013, established an internal Acceleration Fund to encourage rapid experimentation and discovery. The labs allow Citi to pilot new solutions rapidly, search for disruptive business models and focus on emerging technologies, such as blockchain technology and crytpocurrencies. Citi prioritized these labs early on: in 2009 Citi\\u2019s Global Transaction Services business opened it global Research, Development, Innovation and Learning Centre in Dublin. At this time Citi announced an investment of $24 million for the development of a next generation intelligent payments solution bringing Citi\\u2019s total investment in research and development in Ireland to $100 million at that time. Citi has subsequently opened other centers in San Francisco, Israel and Singapore. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>These labs play an important role in allowing Citi to connect its innovation teams with clients, employees and, industry experts. Through showcasing innovation initiatives and solutions, senior management, different business lines, and individuals are engaged with, and exposed to, innovative processes, solutions and mindsets. This is also seen with the Citi Ventures Catalyst program which engages Citi executives to share industry expertise, open conversations, and align strategic interests to help drive the company\\u2019s innovation agenda. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Citi runs multiple accelerator programs in order to engage with startups. Their FinTech accelerator was launched in Tel Aviv in 2013 as part of the Citi Innovation Lab TLV, within Citi\\u2019s global network of innovation centers. Since then, Citi have partnered with Plug and Play to further expand their accelerator programs and engage with FinTech startups. \\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In addition, Citi\\u2019s venture capital arm has grown their Investment portfolio to 23 active startups. Through aligning their investment focus with the core business\\u2019 needs: Big Data and Analytics, Commerce Payments, Financial Technology, Marketing and Customer Experience, and Security and Enterprise IT, Citi seeks to invest in cutting edge and highly relevant startups to drive innovation.&nbsp;&nbsp;<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 09:41:15', '2016-10-27 09:41:15', '73abf913-f354-4d44-8dea-cf5bd87e17b7'),
 ('116', '24', '4', '15', 'en_us', '15', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"How Danske Bank Engages with Over 600 Startups\",\"slug\":\"how-danske-bank-is-making-a-splash-in-the-startup-world\",\"postDate\":1477327740,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"23\"],\"47\":{\"42\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"We partnered with Danske Bank to create TheHub.dk, a platform that aims to relieve the pains of Danish startups and provide a platform for Danske Bank to engage with the startup ecosystem. \",\"image\":[\"37\"]}},\"43\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"A long term perspective on growth and support\",\"text\":\"Danske Bank came to us in the Fall of 2015 with an exciting challenge: to create and run a project that would add value to Danish startups and accelerate the growth of early stage companies.\\u00a0\\r\\n\\r\\nDanske Bank wanted to test new forms of engagement with emerging businesses. By actively participating in the Danish startup ecosystem, they can gain early insights into new technologies and business models that could impact their business in the future.\\r\\n\\r\\nBy supporting startups at an early stage, helping them succeed and grow, the bank would also create a wider stream of potential future customers.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"44\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"After over 100 founder interviews, we found three major pain points faced by Danish startups: \",\"text\":\"1. Recruitment: lack of a nationwide, startup focused job board \\r\\n\\r\\n2. Funding: navigating the overwhelming number of investors and funding options to find the right choice\\r\\n\\r\\n3. Knowledge Sharing: capitalizing on the experience of successful founders to accelerate progress\\r\\n\\r\\nWith these three problems in mind, we created The Hub.\\r\\n\",\"image\":[\"36\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"90\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"An online platform, community and resource center \",\"text\":\"Targeting recruitment first, we built a job board tailored specifically to startups. \\r\\n\\r\\nWe found that startups rely on their own networks and traditional job boards for hiring. But they were missing something fit for purpose. Specifically for entrepreneurs, targeting job seekers interested in joining startups.\\r\\n\\r\\nWe\\u2019ve now created over 550 startup profiles and see over 11000 weekly visits, converting to 600 weekly applications. This is paired with great feedback from both startups and applicants using the site. \",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"120\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"We\\u2019ve now created over 550 startup profiles and see over 11000 weekly visits, converting to 600 weekly applications.\\\"\",\"image\":[\"39\"]}},\"46\":{\"type\":\"quoteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"We received far more applications through the Hub compared to elsewhere. All the applicants were relevant and part of our target group. For those reasons, I would recommend the Hub (and have already done it)\\\"\",\"quoteName\":\"Happy Hub User\",\"role\":\"\",\"image\":[\"39\"]}},\"47\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"To help navigate the funding options available to Danish startups, our next solution was to create a tool which could match startups with the most relevant options for them, based on their industry, experience, level of maturity and team size. This included profiles of the top 50 investors in Denmark.\",\"image\":[\"35\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"48\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Giving Freely\",\"text\":\"Knowledge sharing posed the greatest challenge. The majority of the information startups need is topical, specific to their industry, stage and product. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe Hub therefore needed to address the need for both startup specific, and generic content. To achieve this, we\\u2019ve started to develop a mentor matching scheme to pair startups with relevant advisors. \\r\\n\\r\\nMeanwhile, we\\u2019ve also developed a number of tools to share best practices around some of the steps almost all startups follow.  From raising funds to gaining the very first customers.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"49\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Widening The Hub\\u2019s Reach\",\"text\":\"Today, the Hub is the largest startup recruitment site in Denmark. And, we\\u2019re now applying what we\\u2019ve learned across the Nordics, launching Hubs in Norway and Sweden, opening up opportunities for cross-country applications in markets where Danske Bank is most active.\",\"image\":[\"41\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"166\":{\"type\":\"videoBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"youtubeVideoId\":\"V3RTOLI33Q0\"}}},\"80\":\"1\",\"72\":[\"36\"],\"67\":\"\\u201cWe have partnered with Rainmaking because of their strong foothold in the global startup ecosystem, and their impressive ability to launch and grow new platforms and services at high speed.\\\"\\u00a0\",\"69\":\"Head of Business Innovation\",\"68\":\"Klavs Hjort\",\"71\":[\"22\"]}}', '2016-10-27 09:49:46', '2016-10-27 09:49:46', '581f6a4b-c163-4d5c-88d4-aded13675b54'),
 ('117', '69', '4', '15', 'en_us', '8', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Sourcing Startups to Catapult Castrol\\u2019s Business Forward\",\"slug\":\"strategically-sourcing-startups-to-catapult-castrols-business-forward\",\"postDate\":1477395000,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"64\"],\"47\":{\"74\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Going Beyond Motor Oil\",\"text\":\"In 2012, we were approached by Castrol innoVentures to help increase its deal flow and strengthen its presence and visibility in the global startup community.\\u00a0\\r\\n\\r\\nAt the time, Castrol had just set up its strategic innovation and investment arm in order to bring additional value to its existing business areas, and to take Castrol beyond motor oils and lubricants and into future focused revenue streams.\\r\\n\\r\\nTogether with the team at Castrol innoVentures, we designed a global pitch competition to act as a sourcing and screening program, allowing us to meet and evaluate startups relevant for Castrol to work with. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe program resulted in Castrol making a direct investment in one startup and commercial partnerships with seven others. \",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"71\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"we were approached by Castrol innoVentures to help increase its deal flow and strengthen its presence and visibility in the global startup community.\\\"\",\"image\":[\"68\"]}},\"72\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"How to Put Castrol On the Global Startup Map\",\"text\":\"In today\\u2019s venture capital environment, startups are not short on sources of investment. There are hundreds of institutional firms, angel investors and CVC\\u2019s. \\r\\n\\r\\nWe needed a way to put Castrol on startups\\u2019 radar as a valuable partner, both to work with, and to have on their cap table. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe focus was for us to find startups innovating in 4 strategic areas: Smart Mobility, next generation engineering, intelligent operations, and responsible Castrol.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"75\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Building a Startup Friendly Brand\",\"text\":\"We built a brand around the project: the Castrol 20\\/20 Challenge. Reflecting perfect vision and complete accuracy in finding the right startups for Castrol.\\r\\n\\r\\nA selection of startup finalists would receive free flights and accommodation to London or Shanghai in order to pitch their business to Venture Capitalists and Castrol executives. The winning team was to receive 10,000 USD.\\r\\n\\r\\nA brand website was launched, promoting the competition to potential applicants and spreading the word throughout the global startup community. Both the brand and website were fundamental in positioning Castrol as a company ready to make investments and meaningfully engage with startups.\",\"image\":[\"73\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"76\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"With our marketing efforts driving competition applications, and our dedicated team of researchers, we reviewed over 2,000 startups.\\r\\n\\r\\nDrawing on our experience mentoring and selecting startups for our Startupbootcamp programs and our own investments, we created a shortlist of 20 companies based on their applications and 1-1 interviews.\\r\\n\\r\\nTogether with Castrol innoVentures, we conducted further interviews to narrow the selection to just five startups in each of two competition finals in London and Shanghai.\",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"77\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Preparing startups for collaboration with corporates\",\"text\":\"In both London and Shanghai, we worked with the startups and mentors one day prior to the final events to prepare the teams. We helped them hone their pitches and introduced ways that they could more effectively work with major corporations.  \\r\\n\\r\\nThe following day, the startups pitched and met with over 30 Venture Capitalists, alongside executives from Castrol and other notable corporations like 3M.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe events not only provided immense value to the startups, in terms of connections and networking with experts, but also gave Castrol a platform to engage with the startups early on.\",\"image\":[\"67\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"82\":{\"type\":\"imageBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"images\":[\"79\",\"80\",\"81\"]}},\"78\":{\"type\":\"quoteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"Castrol 2020 Challenge provided impressive and innovative ideas and we work with 7 out of 10 teams from the 2012 program\\\"\",\"quoteName\":\"Roy Williamson\",\"role\":\"Castrol InnoVentures, Managing Director\",\"image\":[\"66\"]}},\"83\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Creating and capitalising on investment opportunities\",\"text\":\"Castrol InnoVentures ultimately invested in Greensteam, a ground breaking technology company specialising in energy saving solutions for commercial vessels.\\r\\n\\r\\nThe events proved to be a success, so we hosted a second edition, this time exclusively in Shanghai.\\r\\n\\r\\nTo this day, Castrol innoVentures remains an active player in the mobility space and has made further investments in a range of startups.\\r\\n\",\"image\":[\"65\"],\"align\":\"left\"}}},\"80\":\"1\",\"72\":[\"65\"],\"67\":\"\\\"The Castrol 20\\/20 Challenge provided impressive and innovative ideas leading to us working with 7 out of 10 startups from the program\\\"\",\"69\":\"Managing Director, Castrol InnoVentures\",\"68\":\"Roy Williamson\",\"71\":[\"66\"]}}', '2016-10-27 09:50:00', '2016-10-27 09:50:00', '724c6749-4e4a-44f7-b03f-4579e1cbe112'),
 ('118', '195', '4', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"How Lloyd\'s Banking Group Stays Ahead of FinTech Evolution\",\"slug\":\"how-lloyds-banking-group-stays-ahead-of-fintech-evolution\",\"postDate\":1477478580,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"178\"],\"47\":{\"196\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Partnering With Market Leaders\",\"text\":\"Since 2014 we have been helping to shape the global evolution of FinTech. Together with market leaders like MasterCard, Lloyds Banking Group, Santander, Thomson Reuters, PWC and Rabobank we are running Startupbootcamp accelerator programs for startups and designing corporate innovation programs, establishing commercial connections between startups and established players.\",\"image\":[\"180\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"198\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"Each year we scout upwards of 3000 FinTech startups from across the globe. With accelerator programs in Singapore, London and New York, and 50+ FinTech events across almost every continent. \",\"image\":[\"179\"]}},\"199\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Early Access to Innovation\",\"text\":\"We select less than 1% of these startups for a Startupbootcamp cohort. This ensures our partners are collaborating with the best talent, often generating pilots, commercial partnerships and co-created solutions. Meanwhile, through the selection process itself, partners are exposed to evolving technology and business model trends at an early stage.  \",\"image\":[\"181\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"200\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Staying in Front of the Curve with Lloyd\'s \",\"text\":\"Lloyds Banking Group has been a partner on our Startupbootcamp FinTech program since 2014. The partnership came at a time when the bank was undertaking a large-scale digital transformation program, and presented an ideal platform to test new ideas and connect with the wider FinTech ecosystem. \",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"201\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"Lloyds\\u2019 goal is to scan the market for innovation and find new opportunities to provide better service to their customers. The relationship is beneficial for both parties: the FinTech startup has access to subject matter experts, launching customers and scarce assets like data sets. For Lloyds it is beneficial because they are able to learn about new technology, business models, see the results within the market and deduce important lessons to stay ahead and deliver value to their customers. \",\"image\":[\"182\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"202\":{\"type\":\"quoteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"The relationship with Startupbootcamp has been the first step towards collaborating with startups and to support our digital transformation agenda. By working with innovative partners we are able to deliver even better customer propositions and services.\",\"quoteName\":\"Claire Calmejane\",\"role\":\"Head of Innovation\",\"image\":[\"189\"]}},\"203\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"Keen to partner with Statupbootcamp\\u2019s portofolio companies, Lloyds has worked with alumni WoraPay \\u2013 a collaboration which is said to have saved Lloyds Banking Group employees 10,000 days of work. \",\"image\":[\"185\"]}},\"204\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"New Ways of Working\",\"text\":\"For Lloyds, collaborating with the FinTech sector also provides inspiring examples of agility and working practices that refresh Lloyd\\u2019s thinking and approach to delivering digital services. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe partnership gave Lloyds the chance to be involved in dedicated events such as FinTech Lounges and hackathons, presenting another opportunity to experience new ways of working.\\r\\n\",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"205\":{\"type\":\"imageBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"images\":[\"191\",\"193\",\"194\"]}}},\"80\":\"1\",\"72\":[\"179\"],\"67\":\"Our relationship with Rainmaking has given hundreds of our employees access to new tools and skillsets that they have used to become inspiring intrepreneurs inside Lloyds Banking Group.\\r\\n\",\"69\":\"Head of Innovation\",\"68\":\"Claire Calmejane\",\"71\":[\"189\"]}}', '2016-10-27 09:50:21', '2016-10-27 09:50:21', '1faa6c05-3ace-4ffc-94d4-c412925e134d'),
 ('119', '57', '4', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Finding the Future of Transportation for Daimler\",\"slug\":\"finding-the-future-of-transportation-for-daimler\",\"postDate\":1477393440,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"70\":[\"51\"],\"47\":{\"58\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Finding the Driving Edge of Startup Talent\",\"text\":\"Daimler, a partner of Startupbootcamp Smart Transportation, owner of Mercedes Benz and the largest commercial vehicle manufacturer in the world, came to us looking for startups that could help them gain an edge against competition and stay up to date on emerging technology.  \\r\\n\\r\\nWe helped them source over 1,000 startups from across 18 countries and identified a number of forces that are shaping the future of transportation and mobility.\",\"image\":[\"50\"],\"align\":\"left\"}},\"59\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Staying In the Fast Lane\",\"text\":\"As cars become connected, electric and autonomous, Daimler recognized that they must identify new innovations early in order to stay at the forefront of current technological advancements. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe challenge was to find the next generation of startups that could help Daimler overtake their competition. \\r\\n\\r\\nWith this in mind, Daimler challenged us to source startup talent, and identify trends that are driving innovation within the smart mobility space. \",\"backgroundColour\":\"grey\"}},\"60\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\\u00a1Hola Brazil!\",\"text\":\"The Rainmaking sourcing team thoroughly screened the global startup market and sourced the best startups that matched our search criteria.  \\r\\n\\r\\nEurope and Brazil offered exciting opportunities, forming the geographic focus for this project.\\r\\n\\r\\nResponding to global trends, we saw that Brazil\\u2019s growth had opened up new markets and created untapped opportunities for startups. In particular, urbanization and rapid population growth present problems that startups were actively finding innovative solutions to. This led us to a new hotbed of talent that was generally underrepresented in mainstream sources.\",\"image\":[\"52\"],\"align\":\"right\"}},\"61\":{\"type\":\"soundbyteBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"text\":\"\\\"Europe and Brazil offered exciting opportunities, forming the geographic focus for this project.\\\"\",\"image\":[\"212\"]}},\"62\":{\"type\":\"textBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"Getting the Whole Picture\",\"text\":\"At the end of the two month sourcing period we had: \\r\\n\\u2022 Sourced companies from 87 separate data sources and 18 countries\\r\\n\\u2022 Reviewed a total of 1759 companies; from startup accelerators to company directors\\r\\n\\u2022 Selected 326 companies for further review, filtering this down to 82\\r\\n\",\"backgroundColour\":\"black\"}},\"63\":{\"type\":\"textBlockWithImages\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"header\":\"\",\"text\":\"Our internal panel reviewed and assessed these startups, refining the selection to a top 40. These were presented back to Daimler alongside a trend report capturing industry insights, further highlighting opportunities for engagement within the startup world.\\r\\n\\r\\nToday Daimler remains actively involved in the startup ecosystem, as a partner in our Smart Transportation & Energy Startupbootcamp and continues to pursue new innovations. \",\"image\":[\"54\"],\"align\":\"right\"}}},\"80\":\"1\",\"72\":[\"56\"],\"67\":\"\\u201cPartnering with Startupbootcamp will accelerate our access to innovation and will plug us into an impressive community of alumni, mentors and investors.\\u201d\",\"69\":\"Senior Manager, Business Innovation\",\"68\":\"Dr. Frank Spennemann\",\"71\":[\"55\"]}}', '2016-10-27 09:50:34', '2016-10-27 09:50:34', 'cc737f18-c932-417a-98b7-ce832b6abdda'),
 ('120', '184', '5', '15', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Bitcoin and Blockchain Investing: Interview with Meltem Demirors of DCG\",\"slug\":\"bitcoin-and-blockchain-investing-interview-with-meltem-demirors-of-dcg\",\"postDate\":1477477140,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"238\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Meltem Demirors, director of community at New York-based&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dcg.co\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Digital Currency Group (DCG)<\\/a>&nbsp;sits down with Startupbootcamp FinTech MD Jesse Podell to discuss the impact of blockchain, the changing nature of venture capital and the reasons she comes to work every morning.<\\/p><p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/_roundPortrait\\/Picture1.png#asset:183:roundPortrait\\\"><br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Where do you see DCG\\u2019s fit in the bitcoin and blockchain ecosystem? Are you the 800 pound gorilla?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;We talked about this a lot when I first joined DCG \\u2013 Why do we come to work in the morning? What inspires us? What motivates us?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I think all of us fundamentally see bitcoin blockchain technology changing the financial system and the broader technology landscape.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>It doesn\\u2019t matter if we\\u2019re the 800 pound gorilla or the small upstart. I think for us we want to have an outsize impact and be an advocate, an evangelist, and the connector that helps make this industry more successful.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Do you see accelerators as a good idea for bitcoin and blockchain startups?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;&nbsp;Yes, absolutely.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One thing I have noticed is that people who have gone through an accelerator program were much better at pitching, were much better at selling the value proposition, and were much better at creating a narrative. That skill set cannot be underestimated. You\\u2019re going through this rigorous program that\\u2019s designed to teach you all of these fantastic skills and competencies, and you\\u2019re learning from some of the best corporate VCs, the best corporate strategists, the best VCs, the best startup mentors that you normally wouldn\\u2019t have access to in your network. It\\u2019s a great way to compress that learning in a really short timeline and to really grow your network and also get great PR. No brainer for me.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Obviously, we\\u2019re super excited to have Startupbootcamp FinTech here and really excited about the startups that will go through your program.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse: &nbsp;What\\u2019s your general advice for startups who might be applying for an accelerator?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;I think people are always a little hesitant about applying. They think: \\u201cOh, it\\u2019s three months away from product development. That\\u2019s difficult. I want to focus on the tech.\\u201d No, no, no, no! Spend three months really getting good at sales, at communicating, at branding, at messaging, building relationships. That is going to do so much more for you than building a great product because growth takes two things. It takes a great product, but it also takes a great sales strategy. Remember that there\\u2019s more to the equation than just the technology and really focus on this opportunity to develop relationships and competencies that are going to help you grow beyond the seed stage.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Where do you see the venture capital model heading in five years?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;I think a lot more people are excited about venture capital. A lot of people want to be investors. It\\u2019s like a sexy thing to do right now, which is great. I love it. The more money that goes into the ecosystem, the more ideas start getting thrown around.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What I think you\\u2019re seeing, though, is a decoupling of the size of the check that an investor\\u2019s able to write and the value that they\\u2019re able to add to an early stage company. We at DCG invest at the seed stage. We aim for 2% to 5% ownership, but we write smaller checks.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What you\\u2019re going to start to see are two different types of investors. You\\u2019re going to see one investor who\\u2019s really focused on network effects, on connectivity, who\\u2019s really focused on value-added services, and another investor that\\u2019s really focused on late stage growth. They\\u2019re going to play two very different roles within the life cycle of a startup.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;What advice would you have for companies who want to pitch DCG?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp; For us, we\\u2019re seed stage investors. What our investing team looks at are three things. Number one, the team. Who are you? What\\u2019s your track record and what\\u2019s your story? Why are you starting this company? We need to see that you have grit and that you have determination and that you really care.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The second is product. Technically, what have you built? Open source software is notoriously competitive, so having teams that are technically competent is very important.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Then the last one is market. How do you think about monetization, and what\\u2019s the timeline on that? We\\u2019re different from most VCs in that we\\u2019re not a fund. We don\\u2019t have a certain timeline. If it\\u2019s going to take you 10 years to reach profitability, I think we\\u2019re okay with that, but you need to have a plan and then you need to have a backup plan and a backup plan to the backup plan.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;What about the role of Community Manager, how do you see it evolving?\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;&nbsp;When I started my role was pretty specific. It was focused on developing better connective tissue between our companies. Now that we have a number of strategic investors on board we started to realize the value of having a broad network. For me, it\\u2019s about building the DCG brand, building relationships, and also creating new opportunities and new ways of thinking around how to internalize innovation within a large organization. &nbsp;It\\u2019s about taking the community role, untangling into the various components that really move the needle and making it more of a discipline.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To read the full interview, please click<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.linkedin.com\\/pulse\\/my-interview-meltem-demirors-dcg-jesse-podell?published=t\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">&nbsp;here<\\/a>:\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Follow&nbsp;Meltem Demirors on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/twitter.com\\/Melt_Dem\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Twitter<\\/a>\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;\\u2013\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dcg.co\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Digital Currency Group&nbsp;<\\/a>manages a large early stage investment portfolio in the digital currency and blockchain space. Recently they announced venture round with a number of leading financial institutions and venture capital firms including MasterCard, Bain Capital Ventures, New York Life and RRE Ventures. &nbsp;The firm had already established itself as a predominant investor of early stage bitcoin startups, with over 50 holdings currently in its portfolio.\\r\\n\\r\\n  <\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 09:58:22', '2016-10-27 09:58:22', '95ab1043-b1e8-4570-a286-3d85be13b8b7'),
 ('121', '146', '5', '15', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Missed Connections in the Sandbox\",\"slug\":\"missed-connections-in-the-sandbox\",\"postDate\":1477413360,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"145\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>This week, industry thought leaders from incumbent banks and FinTech startups gathered in the Rainmaking Loft for the first in the Autumn Season for the Rainmaking Sessions\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a<em>Playing in the sandbox<\\/em>. The session looked at the establishment of the Regulatory Sandbox run by the Financial Conduct Authority and the appetite and capability of many incumbent banks to participate in the new scheme and partner with new entrants to the financial services landscape.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The outcome? There are many footprints in the sandbox, but many may have to wait some time for impressive castles to be built.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA\\u2019s Regulatory Sandbox is meant to be a legal framework or a \\u2018safe space\\u2019 where businesses can test innovative products, services, business models and delivery mechanisms. This is a progressive step for startups in regulated industries, like financial services. However, many young companies still need active partnerships with established banks, firms and other corporates in order to test developing products with live data, enterprise architecture and an active customer base.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Sandboxes, like the one set up by the FCA in the UK, are a step in the right direction for regulated industries. But they struggle to be useful if certain startups aren\\u2019t given the resources to test their products, properly.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA sandbox was designed to allow for collaboration. Currently, there are many FinTech startups involved in the programme. The FCA does not make public the names or the number of startups participating in the sandbox. However, many of these companies still require participation from incumbent banks in order to adequately test their offerings in the safe legal framework the FCA has established.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>However many banks, themselves, are working on creating their own innovation labs to not only support and welcome new technology and services entrants, but to enable and empower their own internal staff to embrace innovation. Many in this industry know that incumbent banks and financial services firms move at a pace considered much slower than is enjoyed in the Silicon Valley-style startup world. This is true even for banks that are working towards creating a more agile and flexible work environment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The window of opportunity is open now to work within the FCA Regulatory Sandbox. This time around the pace of change and collaboration may be more \\u2018missed connections\\u2019 than Match.com.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 10:01:20', '2016-10-27 10:01:20', 'bfe81cc6-3da9-473a-88f2-6ae99145e582'),
 ('122', '240', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Innovation Culture In Companies \\u2013 Easier Said Than Done?\",\"slug\":\"innovation-culture-in-companies-easier-said-than-done\",\"postDate\":1477562760,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"239\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Innovation is the new buzzword these days. Major corporates are tuning their inhouse hierarchy to fit in \\u201cinnovation\\u201d in their culture, vision and value. To an extent that nowadays, there is a specific job title in major healthcare conglomerates called, \\u201cChief Innovation Officer\\u201d to build innovation cultures in the company.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>So what exactly is an Innovation culture, and why is it suddenly a necessity? Let us explore this and its role specifically in the field of healthcare.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation Culture is a company environment chosen by the leaders to encourage and facilitate unorthodox ideas and strategies. In these companies, innovation is not just a privilege of the C-level, but employee at any level is encouraged to foster the culture and be innovative in their approach.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>So why is it suddenly a necessity?<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Many companies working the traditional way for decades now suddenly are shifting towards innovation cultures. There are several factors contributing to this shift.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The primary reason for this shift is Digitalization. Digitalization has paced up the market, the customer has a strong voice and bad performance instantly gets bad reviews. Hence, the scope of error has reduced hugely, making it paramount for companies to invent new ways of customer satisfaction.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The second factor weighing in is the rise of startups. Startups are agile and flexible, they are not afraid to be different and to try a road not taken, because they have nothing to lose. Large corporates, on the other hand, have much to lose if they try something that is not a standard norm.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The third and the most crucial factor is the consumer market. Consumers have changed, trust is still valuable but so is creativity. Market models have changed and even the old and established market structures are undergoing a change. This makes innovation paramount.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>But what does innovation culture comprise of?<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation Culture is not a pet project, it is a style of thinking. It is not a creative inborn talent, it is a practiced skill. Which also means that there is not set way or rules to this culture, but every team builds its own culture. Here are some factors we see overlapping in all companies fostering Innovation Culture.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>1.Speed<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The need of innovation arises from fast &nbsp;changing market needs, hence shorter innovation cycles are paramount. Speculation over long time leads to slowness, the very evil corporations are trying to avoid. However, speed needs to come from quick decision making and clarity in vision, and not rash decisions.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>2.Digitalization<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Digitalization is one of the primary reasons behind the shift in markets. So it is imperative for corporates to not just add but make digitalization an integral part of their outreach plan. The consumer expects companies to fill gaps and be more service oriented, and digitalization is the fastest way to address this need.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>3. Open leadership<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>While it is important for the company founders and leaders to value and encourage innovation cultures, in successful innovation culture implementation, lower management also believes and practices an open creative culture, as these are the people who function directly with execution and micro manage teams.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>4.Value in failure<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One reason why corporations fail at innovation is because they are risk averse. They are big and protecting the name becomes more and more important. But as one adopts innovation culture, one needs to learn the art of accepting failure. An interesting take is to call a Failure a \\u201cglitch\\u201d. While a failure sounds painfully permanent, a glitch sounds temporary, solvable and a learning opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>5.Sustaining innovation<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>It is a tough task to get your employees to embrace innovation culture, but it is equally important to get them to stay on course. It can not be just a one-project affair. To get employees to show innovativity in workplace, there can be rewards, from as big as a holiday to as tiny as sincere appreciation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>6.Flat hierarchy<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Flat hierarchy is a fast-evolving management style that many companies are adopting. Some people call it Bossless Management, some call it Radical Management and some, Holacracy, but the core of the concept remains the same. The concept does away with leadership\\u2019s sole decision making power and gives the power to the collective intelligence of all employees. One good example of Holacracy is&nbsp;###a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/searchcio.techtarget.com\\/feature\\/Flap-over-Zappos-holacracy-puts-spotlight-on-bossless-workplace\\\"&gt;Zappos, one of the largest companies to have adopted bossless administration.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>All innovative companies have different missions, but their processes are similar. They encourage unorthodox methods that include speed, flexibility, adaptation of digital technology, flat hierarchies and sustainable innovation.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 10:06:47', '2016-10-27 10:06:47', '848e07f7-870a-43b9-abae-51120d9e7afb'),
 ('123', '242', '5', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"These 3 Trends Are Revolutionizing Mobility\",\"slug\":\"these-3-trends-are-revolutionizing-mobility\",\"postDate\":1477563630,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"241\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>The urban transportation landscape is in the midst of massive change. Now, if you were sitting in your car waiting in traffic this morning, you might be thinking, \\u201cyeah, right\\u201d. Though if your car is not the only way you travel, you might have experienced the changes for yourself. In European cities such as Berlin, alternative urban mobility services such as car sharing have&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">decreased the dominance<\\/a>&nbsp;of car ownership as the main method of urban transportation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Car2go, Uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from A to B. That is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant. Indeed&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">73% of households<\\/a>&nbsp;in Berlin still own at least one car. Needless to say, if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable, we still have a long way to go. There are, however, trends that are spurring on this shift. We\\u2019ll take a closer look at three of them: smartphone adoption, urbanization, and \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Smartphone Adoption<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>###p<at the=\\\"\\\" 2016=\\\"\\\" city=\\\"\\\" car=\\\"\\\" summit=\\\"\\\" in=\\\"\\\" berlin,=\\\"\\\" dr.=\\\"\\\" wolfgang=\\\"\\\" gruel,=\\\"\\\" head=\\\"\\\" of=\\\"\\\" autonomous=\\\"\\\" mobility=\\\"\\\" services=\\\"\\\" at=\\\"\\\" car2go,=\\\"\\\" claimed=\\\"\\\" that=\\\"\\\" single=\\\"\\\" biggest=\\\"\\\" innovation=\\\"\\\" is=\\\"\\\" smartphone.=\\\"\\\" looking=\\\"\\\" latest=\\\"\\\" we=\\\"\\\" use=\\\"\\\" today,=\\\"\\\" it\\u2019s=\\\"\\\" easy=\\\"\\\" to=\\\"\\\" agree.=\\\"\\\" smartphones=\\\"\\\" have=\\\"\\\" enabled=\\\"\\\" new=\\\"\\\" business=\\\"\\\" models=\\\"\\\" multiple=\\\"\\\" areas=\\\"\\\" shared=\\\"\\\" such=\\\"\\\" as=\\\"\\\" sharing=\\\"\\\" (car2go,=\\\"\\\" zipcar),=\\\"\\\" ridesharing=\\\"\\\" (lyft,=\\\"\\\" blablacar),=\\\"\\\" and=\\\"\\\" taxi=\\\"\\\" (uber,=\\\"\\\" blacklane).=\\\"\\\" also=\\\"\\\" led=\\\"\\\" launch=\\\"\\\" apps=\\\"\\\" (moovel,=\\\"\\\" ally)=\\\"\\\" help=\\\"\\\" us=\\\"\\\" decide=\\\"\\\" what=\\\"\\\" our=\\\"\\\" most=\\\"\\\" convenient=\\\"\\\" efficient=\\\"\\\" way=\\\"\\\" travel=\\\"\\\" is.<=\\\"\\\" p=\\\"\\\"><br><\\/at><\\/p><p>In Germany, the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise. According to&nbsp;###a href=\\\"<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Germany-Posts-Big-Increase-Mobile-Internet-Use\\/1011884#sthash.vNbOGCYz.dpuf\\\">data\\\" class=\\\"redactor-linkify-object\\\"&gt;http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Artic...<\\/a> from emarketer, in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the Internet in comparison to 40% in 2013. In addition,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">28% of Berlin residents<\\/a>&nbsp;use travel apps with their smartphones daily, while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week. The further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Urbanization<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Urbanization is a global megatrend.&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/geos\\/gm.html\\\">Over 75% of the population<\\/a>&nbsp;of Germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cinum.org\\/en\\/urbanisation-mobility\\/88-90-114.html\\\">60% of the world\\u2019s population<\\/a>&nbsp;will live in cities. Combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit, and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities. Due to this charging urban environment, car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support. The risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren\\u2019t open to, and supportive of, mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to. In addition to changes in public policy, we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life. This topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\u201cAccess over Ownership\\u201d<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ted.com\\/talks\\/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\\\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman<\\/a>, people are \\u201cwired to share.\\u201d In her book&nbsp;What\\u2019s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership\\/1012429\\\">report by PricewaterhouseCoopers<\\/a>supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends \\u2013 smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership \\u2013 will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2015\\/11\\/17\\/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars\\/\\\">George Arison wrote<\\/a>: \\u201cAnd anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.\\u201d Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn\\u2019t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we\\u2019ll be watching the latest developments very closely.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\"}}', '2016-10-27 10:20:30', '2016-10-27 10:20:30', '98f28a6d-2264-4a7b-8ad7-54e77793b906'),
 ('124', '242', '5', '15', 'en_us', '2', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"These 3 Trends Are Revolutionizing Mobility\",\"slug\":\"these-3-trends-are-revolutionizing-mobility\",\"postDate\":1477563600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"241\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>The urban transportation landscape is in the midst of massive change. Now, if you were sitting in your car waiting in traffic this morning, you might be thinking, \\u201cyeah, right\\u201d. Though if your car is not the only way you travel, you might have experienced the changes for yourself. In European cities such as Berlin, alternative urban mobility services such as car sharing have&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">decreased the dominance<\\/a>&nbsp;of car ownership as the main method of urban transportation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Car2go, Uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from A to B. That is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant. Indeed&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">73% of households<\\/a>&nbsp;in Berlin still own at least one car. Needless to say, if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable, we still have a long way to go. There are, however, trends that are spurring on this shift. We\\u2019ll take a closer look at three of them: smartphone adoption, urbanization, and \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Smartphone Adoption<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>###p<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In Germany, the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise. According to <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Germany-Posts-Big-Increase-Mobile-Internet-Use\\/1011884#sthash.vNbOGCYz.dpuf\\\">data&nbsp;from emarketer<\\/a>, in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the Internet in comparison to 40% in 2013. In addition,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">28% of Berlin residents<\\/a>&nbsp;use travel apps with their smartphones daily, while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week. The further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Urbanization<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Urbanization is a global megatrend.&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/geos\\/gm.html\\\">Over 75% of the population<\\/a>&nbsp;of Germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cinum.org\\/en\\/urbanisation-mobility\\/88-90-114.html\\\">60% of the world\\u2019s population<\\/a>&nbsp;will live in cities. Combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit, and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities. Due to this charging urban environment, car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support. The risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren\\u2019t open to, and supportive of, mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to. In addition to changes in public policy, we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life. This topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\u201cAccess over Ownership\\u201d<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ted.com\\/talks\\/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\\\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman<\\/a>, people are \\u201cwired to share.\\u201d In her book&nbsp;What\\u2019s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership\\/1012429\\\">report by PricewaterhouseCoopers<\\/a>supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends \\u2013 smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership \\u2013 will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2015\\/11\\/17\\/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars\\/\\\">George Arison wrote<\\/a>: \\u201cAnd anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.\\u201d Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn\\u2019t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we\\u2019ll be watching the latest developments very closely.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-27 10:22:40', '2016-10-27 10:22:40', '665bc2cc-08e3-4aeb-8564-a97745c392f6'),
 ('125', '243', '3', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"The Rainmaking Sessions - Playing in the sandbox\",\"slug\":\"the-rainmaking-sessions-playing-in-the-sandbox\",\"postDate\":1477564612,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"25\":\"1 St. Katherine\'s Way, London, E1W 1UN\",\"1\":\"<p>Playing in the sandbox&nbsp;-&nbsp;<i>Can co-creation, between startups and incumbents, be the key to building successful products?<\\/i>\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This year the Financial Conduct Authority launched the Regulatory Sandbox, which is meant to be a \\u2018safe space\\u2019 where businesses can test innovative products, services, business models and delivery mechanisms. This is a progressive step for startups in regulated industries, like financial services. However, many young companies still need active partnerships with established banks, firms and other corporates in order to test developing products with live data, enterprise architecture and an active customer base.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Sandboxes, like the one set up by the FCA in the UK, are a step in the right direction for regulated industries. But they struggle to be useful if certain startups aren\\u2019t given the resources to test their products, properly. What incentives can you give traditional firms to invite them into the sandbox to support startups to co-create industry-changing products? What procedures can you put in place to make sure co-creation is not only beneficial to startups, incumbents firms but to the regulatory process itself?\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><i>Playing in the sandbox,&nbsp;<\\/i>will be an interactive, think tank style roundtable where you can hear from industry experts to debate and discuss the current state of the industry as well as future trends with your peers.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Please join us at the Rainmaking Loft to be a part of this series of thought provoking Rainmaking Sessions, trends that are shaping our industry.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>You will hear from:&nbsp;\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li>Anna Wallace,&nbsp;Manager, Innovation Hub at the Financial Conduct Authority\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Jon Pearson, London Lab Manager, Deutsche Bank Labs\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Agenda:\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li>8:15 - Arrival at loft for coffee\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><li>8:30 \\u2013 Buffet style breakfast served\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><li>8:45 - Welcome and talks begin\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><li>9:15 - Moderated Roundtable starts\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><li>10:30 - Breakfast Roundtable ends\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Spaces are limited, so please register with EventBrite for your chance to be a part of this special event.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Once you reserve your place, please shout about your attendance by sharing \\u2018I will be adding my views and insights to the #RainmakingSessions on&nbsp;<i>Playing in the sandbox on 11&nbsp;<\\/i>October!\\u2019 on your social media channels.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The Rainmaking Sessions\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><i>The Rainmaking Sessions<\\/i><i>&nbsp;are series of monthly, breakfast roundtables to foster debate, discussion and discourse on the nature of innovation in corporates, FinTech, InsurTech, Digital Health and Smart Transportation.<\\/i>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"23\":\"https:\\/\\/www.eventbrite.co.uk\\/e\\/playing-in-the-sandbox-tickets-27541673888\",\"73\":[\"104\"],\"24\":\"Rainmaking Loft - London\",\"26\":{\"date\":\"10\\/11\\/2016\",\"time\":\"8:00 AM\"}}}', '2016-10-27 10:36:53', '2016-10-27 10:36:53', '0d2755f1-f9ab-4e1f-8741-a570c4b7dcd9'),
 ('126', '245', '3', '15', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Innovation in the financial supply chain\",\"slug\":\"innovation-in-the-financial-supply-chain\",\"postDate\":1477570220,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"25\":\"1 St. Katherine\'s Way, London, E1W 1UN\",\"1\":\"<p>Innovation in the financial supply chain&nbsp;\\u2013&nbsp;<em>How can banks find opportunities for innovation in the changing face of the supply chain?<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In the post-digital, global economy, corporate and commercial clients are both importers and exporters; supply chains are deeper and more fragmented and access to trade credit is being squeezed. The International Chamber of Commerce (ICC) Standard Definitions for Techniques of Supply Chain Finance pave the way for greater adoption and commonality in supply chain finance and bank assisted open account offerings.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Supply chains for many of your corporate clients are multi-layered and complex, with difficulties in obtaining visibility, connectivity or sufficient risk information across all parties involved. Visibility of the so-called \\u201clong tail\\u201d is crucial for reducing transaction risk. In many areas, supply chains are getting shorter and they need to be dynamic, fast, agile and data-centric. The emergence of cloud platforms, new marketplaces, eDocs and new standards now provide the ecosystem for banks and new entrants to revolutionise the market. But collaboration is king.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Innovation in the financial supply chain<\\/em>, will be an interactive, think tank style roundtable, sponsored by Misys. Industry experts and supply chain professionals will debate and discuss the current state of the industry as well as future trends.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Please join us at the Rainmaking Loft to be a part of this series of thought-provoking Rainmaking Sessions, on trends that are shaping our industry.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\