a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ted.com\\/talks\\/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\\\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman<\\/a>, people are \\u201cwired to share.\\u201d In her book&nbsp;What\\u2019s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership\\/1012429\\\">report by PricewaterhouseCoopers<\\/a>supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends \\u2013 smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership \\u2013 will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2015\\/11\\/17\\/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars\\/\\\">George Arison wrote<\\/a>: \\u201cAnd anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.\\u201d Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn\\u2019t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we\\u2019ll be watching the latest developments very closely.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-10-31 11:46:36', '2016-10-31 11:46:36', 'cdfcafad-2d21-4a48-886a-54e2550b06da'),
