d new business models that can transform the enterprise. While keeping a foot inside a company, keeps lines of communication and collaboration open with senior people at the firm.<\\/p><p>This line of talk moved onto a debate on whether innovation departments need to be centralised, and separate from the main organisation, with their own staff, budget and authority or decentralised. The centralised model had the advantages of a separate budget line which would allow projects to develop without relying on the P&L of separate business units. The decentralised approach emphasised the importance of encouraging the entire firm to engage in innovation projects and activities.<\\/p><p>Innovation tends to signal change for most companies and change is scary. People and culture are key to ensuring that establishing and innovation culture is seen as beneficial and empowering to the rest of the organisation.<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/1KuyS3TbSOtuUIL3loV17JA.png#asset:140:url\\\" alt=\\\"1KuyS3TbSOtuUIL3loV17JA.png#asset:140\\\"><\\/p><p>Many around the Rainmaking Session breakfast table recognised that a large number of&nbsp;innovation projects were led by either senior management or staff working hands on in development. It was the so-called \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 that was most in need of empowerment when it came to innovation. A large proportion of the group argued that this \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 was not incentivised to try anything new or to embark on innovation projects that have the possibility of failure embedded in its DNA.<\\/p><p>Innovation projects are hard to measure, and including metrics at all might be detrimental to its successes. However, most large corporates operate in a risk culture that requires performance metrics and measurement. The \\u2018can\\u2019t live with metrics\\/can\\u2019t live without metrics\\u2019 debate continues.<\\/p><h2>Advice to Startups<\\/h2><p>Finally, the roundtable debate focuse