 ('355', '7', '7', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"7\",\"authorId\":null,\"title\":\"Who We Are\",\"slug\":\"who-we-are\",\"postDate\":1477583928,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"63\":\"Everyone at Rainmaking lives and breathes the entrepreneurial spirit. We started in 2006 as a collective of serial entrepreneurs, sharing in the both the risks and the rewards of starting new businesses. Since then, we have grown into a global community of entrepreneurs, investors and ex-corporate executives. Driven to create something new, to make a difference.  \"}}', '2016-11-15 16:59:29', '2016-11-15 16:59:29', '80d4ae0d-0a7a-43bf-9e11-d90873502fb3'),
 ('356', '242', '5', '15', 'en_us', '16', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"These 3 Trends Are Revolutionizing Mobility\",\"slug\":\"these-3-trends-are-revolutionizing-mobility\",\"postDate\":1477563600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"241\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Car2go, Uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from A to B. That is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant. Indeed&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">73% of households<\\/a>&nbsp;in Berlin still own at least one car. Needless to say, if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable, we still have a long way to go. There are, however, trends that are spurring on this shift. We\\u2019ll take a closer look at three of them: smartphone adoption, urbanization, and \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<span><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In Germany, the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise. According to <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Germany-Posts-Big-Increase-Mobile-Internet-Use\\/1011884#sthash.vNbOGCYz.dpuf\\\">data&nbsp;from emarketer<\\/a>, in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the Internet in comparison to 40% in 2013. In addition,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">28% of Berlin residents<\\/a>&nbsp;use travel apps with their smartphones daily, while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week. The further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology.<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Urbanization<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Urbanization is a global megatrend.&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/geos\\/gm.html\\\">Over 75% of the population<\\/a>&nbsp;of Germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cinum.org\\/en\\/urbanisation-mobility\\/88-90-114.html\\\">60% of the world\\u2019s population<\\/a>&nbsp;will live in cities. Combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit, and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities. Due to this charging urban environment, car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support. The risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren\\u2019t open to, and supportive of, mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to. In addition to changes in public policy, we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life. This topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>\\u201cAccess over Ownership\\u201d<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ted.com\\/talks\\/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\\\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman<\\/a>, people are \\u201cwired to share.\\u201d In her book&nbsp;What\\u2019s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership\\/1012429\\\">report by PricewaterhouseCoopers<\\/a>supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends \\u2013 smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership \\u2013 will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2015\\/11\\/17\\/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars\\/\\\">George Arison wrote<\\/a>: \\u201cAnd anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.\\u201d Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn\\u2019t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we\\u2019ll be watching the latest developments very closely.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:07:53', '2016-11-15 17:07:53', 'ccf05fed-ae4e-43ff-8819-f57ba6f1231c'),
 ('357', '242', '5', '15', 'en_us', '17', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"348\",\"title\":\"These 3 Trends Are Revolutionizing Mobility\",\"slug\":\"these-3-trends-are-revolutionizing-mobility\",\"postDate\":1477563600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"241\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Car2go, Uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from A to B. That is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant. Indeed&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">73% of households<\\/a>&nbsp;in Berlin still own at least one car. Needless to say, if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable, we still have a long way to go. There are, however, trends that are spurring on this shift. We\\u2019ll take a closer look at three of them: smartphone adoption, urbanization, and \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<span><\\/span><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In Germany, the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise. According to <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Germany-Posts-Big-Increase-Mobile-Internet-Use\\/1011884#sthash.vNbOGCYz.dpuf\\\">data&nbsp;from emarketer<\\/a>, in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the Internet in comparison to 40% in 2013. In addition,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/files.lsecities.net\\/files\\/2015\\/09\\/New-Urban-Mobility-London-and-Berlin.pdf\\\">28% of Berlin residents<\\/a>&nbsp;use travel apps with their smartphones daily, while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week. The further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology.<br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Urbanization<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Urbanization is a global megatrend.&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.cia.gov\\/library\\/publications\\/the-world-factbook\\/geos\\/gm.html\\\">Over 75% of the population<\\/a>&nbsp;of Germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cinum.org\\/en\\/urbanisation-mobility\\/88-90-114.html\\\">60% of the world\\u2019s population<\\/a>&nbsp;will live in cities. Combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit, and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities. Due to this charging urban environment, car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support. The risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren\\u2019t open to, and supportive of, mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to. In addition to changes in public policy, we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life. This topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>\\u201cAccess over Ownership\\u201d<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.ted.com\\/talks\\/rachel_botsman_the_case_for_collaborative_consumption?language=en#t-80279\\\">According to researcher Rachel Botsman<\\/a>, people are \\u201cwired to share.\\u201d In her book&nbsp;What\\u2019s Mine Is Yours: The Rise of Collaborative Consumption, she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way. A&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.emarketer.com\\/Article\\/Sharing-Economy-Users-Desire-Access-Over-Ownership\\/1012429\\\">report by PricewaterhouseCoopers<\\/a>supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose \\u201caccess over ownership\\u201d.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past? The trends \\u2013 smartphone adoption, urbanization, and access over ownership \\u2013 will certainly play their part, but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>TechCrunch journalist&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2015\\/11\\/17\\/yes-millennials-do-buy-cars\\/\\\">George Arison wrote<\\/a>: \\u201cAnd anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an Uber can tell you, there is nothing quite like owning your own car, especially when you become a parent.\\u201d Uber revolutionized transportation, but the service today isn\\u2019t a silver bullet. The market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions. And you can be sure we\\u2019ll be watching the latest developments very closely.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:13:35', '2016-11-15 17:13:35', 'bfe1e007-9018-44dd-9e1e-873f8fef6d0b'),
