 ('359', '240', '5', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"349\",\"title\":\"Innovation Culture In Companies \\u2013 Easier Said Than Done?\",\"slug\":\"innovation-culture-in-companies-easier-said-than-done\",\"postDate\":1477562760,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"239\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Innovation is the new buzzword these days. Major corporates are tuning their inhouse hierarchy to fit in \\u201cinnovation\\u201d in their culture, vision and value. To an extent that nowadays, there is a specific job title in major healthcare conglomerates called, \\u201cChief Innovation Officer\\u201d to build innovation cultures in the company.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>So what exactly is an Innovation culture, and why is it suddenly a necessity? Let us explore this and its role specifically in the field of healthcare.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation Culture is a company environment chosen by the leaders to encourage and facilitate unorthodox ideas and strategies. In these companies, innovation is not just a privilege of the C-level, but employee at any level is encouraged to foster the culture and be innovative in their approach.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>So why is it suddenly a necessity?<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Many companies working the traditional way for decades now suddenly are shifting towards innovation cultures. There are several factors contributing to this shift.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The primary reason for this shift is Digitalization. Digitalization has paced up the market, the customer has a strong voice and bad performance instantly gets bad reviews. Hence, the scope of error has reduced hugely, making it paramount for companies to invent new ways of customer satisfaction.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The second factor weighing in is the rise of startups. Startups are agile and flexible, they are not afraid to be different and to try a road not taken, because they have nothing to lose. Large corporates, on the other hand, have much to lose if they try something that is not a standard norm.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The third and the most crucial factor is the consumer market. Consumers have changed, trust is still valuable but so is creativity. Market models have changed and even the old and established market structures are undergoing a change. This makes innovation paramount.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>But what does innovation culture comprise of?<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation Culture is not a pet project, it is a style of thinking. It is not a creative inborn talent, it is a practiced skill. Which also means that there is not set way or rules to this culture, but every team builds its own culture. Here are some factors we see overlapping in all companies fostering Innovation Culture.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>1.&nbsp;Speed<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The need of innovation arises from fast &nbsp;changing market needs, hence shorter innovation cycles are paramount. Speculation over long time leads to slowness, the very evil corporations are trying to avoid. However, speed needs to come from quick decision making and clarity in vision, and not rash decisions.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>2.&nbsp;Digitalization<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Digitalization is one of the primary reasons behind the shift in markets. So it is imperative for corporates to not just add but make digitalization an integral part of their outreach plan. The consumer expects companies to fill gaps and be more service oriented, and digitalization is the fastest way to address this need.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>3. Open leadership<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>While it is important for the company founders and leaders to value and encourage innovation cultures, in successful innovation culture implementation, lower management also believes and practices an open creative culture, as these are the people who function directly with execution and micro manage teams.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>4.&nbsp;Value in failure<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One reason why corporations fail at innovation is because they are risk averse. They are big and protecting the name becomes more and more important. But as one adopts innovation culture, one needs to learn the art of accepting failure. An interesting take is to call a Failure a \\u201cglitch\\u201d. While a failure sounds painfully permanent, a glitch sounds temporary, solvable and a learning opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>5.&nbsp;Sustaining innovation<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>It is a tough task to get your employees to embrace innovation culture, but it is equally important to get them to stay on course. It can not be just a one-project affair. To get employees to show innovativity in workplace, there can be rewards, from as big as a holiday to as tiny as sincere appreciation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>6.&nbsp;Flat hierarchy<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Flat hierarchy is a fast-evolving management style that many companies are adopting. Some people call it Bossless Management, some call it Radical Management and some, Holacracy, but the core of the concept remains the same. The concept does away with leadership\\u2019s sole decision making power and gives the power to the collective intelligence of all employees. One good example of Holacracy is&nbsp;###a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/searchcio.techtarget.com\\/feature\\/Flap-over-Zappos-holacracy-puts-spotlight-on-bossless-workplace\\\"&gt;Zappos, one of the largest companies to have adopted bossless administration.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>All innovative companies have different missions, but their processes are similar. They encourage unorthodox methods that include speed, flexibility, adaptation of digital technology, flat hierarchies and sustainable innovation.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:20:50', '2016-11-15 17:20:50', 'f037244a-4930-4d2d-9cb8-9f00efd7a82b'),
 ('360', '237', '5', '15', 'en_us', '9', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"\",\"title\":\"Video: Who Are Rainmaking?\",\"slug\":\"who-are-rainmaking\",\"postDate\":1477558860,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"224\"],\"17\":[\"shortForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Rainmaking Innovation partner, Nektarios Liolios explains what we are all about here at Rainmaking and gives an inside look into some of the ways that we are approaching corporate innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<div class=\\\"video-container\\\"><iframe src=\\\"\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/c9Y0Zlm1Puc\\\" frameborder=\\\"0\\\" allowfullscreen=\\\"\\\"><\\/iframe><\\/div>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Read the full transcript below.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Interview with Nektarios Liolios<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My name is Nektarios Liolios, I\'m one of the partners of Rainmaking Innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What we do a Rainmaking Innovation is we help corporates find ways to innovate, as simple as that.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>People joke about the Kodak moments but, there is a Kodak moment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The frustration that we see is organizations who are so conservative they actually don\'t understand that if they don\'t move faster they\'re actually running a real risk of failing, of disappearing.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The biggest challenge corporates face with innovation is that they actually don\'t know&nbsp;what they\'re doing. They get very excited, they also feel a lot of pressure to do something and then they randomly do things.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One of the trends that we see, is organizations recognizing that working with startups is one channel but building products startup style is another, so the trend is really focusing on closing that loop. That\'s one of the things we see, the other one is really diversification. So, looking at innovation, not a box ticking exercise, but it\'s something that has to have many different iterations and many different facets.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>On the positive side, we see organizations trying a variety of different things; setting up their own investment funds, working with accelerators, doing their own incubation initiatives, having very structured programs for themselves. But also, putting a lot of effort into internal innovation initiatives by educating people about change, by giving them the opportunity to see other ways of working by giving them the opportunity to collaborate with competitors.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The smart organizations recognize that they need to do multiple things at the same time and they need to allow themselves to fail. They also need to connect the internal and external innovation efforts. If you just take startup engagement for instance; startups come in different stages and they have different needs and also different benefits for the organization. So, you can be part of an accelerator to see very early stage startups, to get excited by the the spirit and the drive and the passion of entrepreneurs, but also just to see the very latest trends.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When it comes to using real technology that has been built by startups then you have to look at something that is maybe a little bit more advanced, maybe a little bit more mature, but that engagement has to be different. Maybe it\'s more like a managed lab, maybe it\'s trying to find ways of incorporating the technology into the business. And this is something that often happens by exploring. By using something like a startup studio, something like a separate entity, separate organization, that is bringing people together with startup experience and putting them together with project people from the organization who know about the business.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The interesting thing in this new and evolving landscape is that organizations still sometimes cling on to the idea of \\u201cwe have to do everything ourselves,\\u201d and the smarter organizations recognize that there\'s certain things that you cannot do as a bank, as an insurer, as a large corporate by yourself. Because you don\'t have the know how, you don\'t have the expertise; but also, when It comes to collaboration, which is really important in this space, you usually cannot easily collaborate, by yourself, with other parties. So, having a neutral organization, having somebody like a startupbootcamp who would come in the middle, who brings people around the table and gets them to openly share their challenges, share their problems and priorities, and get them to jointly engage with startups is something that we\'ve seen being very successful.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:21:47', '2016-11-15 17:21:47', '1748c812-674d-459d-adda-f78885fe66af'),
 ('361', '237', '5', '15', 'en_us', '10', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"Video: Who Are Rainmaking?\",\"slug\":\"who-are-rainmaking\",\"postDate\":1477558860,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"224\"],\"17\":[\"shortForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Rainmaking Innovation partner, Nektarios Liolios explains what we are all about here at Rainmaking and gives an inside look into some of the ways that we are approaching corporate innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<div class=\\\"video-container\\\"><iframe src=\\\"\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/c9Y0Zlm1Puc\\\" frameborder=\\\"0\\\" allowfullscreen=\\\"\\\"><\\/iframe><\\/div>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Read the full transcript below.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h1>Interview with Nektarios Liolios<\\/h1>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My name is Nektarios Liolios, I\'m one of the partners of Rainmaking Innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What we do a Rainmaking Innovation is we help corporates find ways to innovate, as simple as that.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>People joke about the Kodak moments but, there is a Kodak moment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The frustration that we see is organizations who are so conservative they actually don\'t understand that if they don\'t move faster they\'re actually running a real risk of failing, of disappearing.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The biggest challenge corporates face with innovation is that they actually don\'t know&nbsp;what they\'re doing. They get very excited, they also feel a lot of pressure to do something and then they randomly do things.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One of the trends that we see, is organizations recognizing that working with startups is one channel but building products startup style is another, so the trend is really focusing on closing that loop. That\'s one of the things we see, the other one is really diversification. So, looking at innovation, not a box ticking exercise, but it\'s something that has to have many different iterations and many different facets.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>On the positive side, we see organizations trying a variety of different things; setting up their own investment funds, working with accelerators, doing their own incubation initiatives, having very structured programs for themselves. But also, putting a lot of effort into internal innovation initiatives by educating people about change, by giving them the opportunity to see other ways of working by giving them the opportunity to collaborate with competitors.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The smart organizations recognize that they need to do multiple things at the same time and they need to allow themselves to fail. They also need to connect the internal and external innovation efforts. If you just take startup engagement for instance; startups come in different stages and they have different needs and also different benefits for the organization. So, you can be part of an accelerator to see very early stage startups, to get excited by the the spirit and the drive and the passion of entrepreneurs, but also just to see the very latest trends.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When it comes to using real technology that has been built by startups then you have to look at something that is maybe a little bit more advanced, maybe a little bit more mature, but that engagement has to be different. Maybe it\'s more like a managed lab, maybe it\'s trying to find ways of incorporating the technology into the business. And this is something that often happens by exploring. By using something like a startup studio, something like a separate entity, separate organization, that is bringing people together with startup experience and putting them together with project people from the organization who know about the business.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The interesting thing in this new and evolving landscape is that organizations still sometimes cling on to the idea of \\u201cwe have to do everything ourselves,\\u201d and the smarter organizations recognize that there\'s certain things that you cannot do as a bank, as an insurer, as a large corporate by yourself. Because you don\'t have the know how, you don\'t have the expertise; but also, when It comes to collaboration, which is really important in this space, you usually cannot easily collaborate, by yourself, with other parties. So, having a neutral organization, having somebody like a startupbootcamp who would come in the middle, who brings people around the table and gets them to openly share their challenges, share their problems and priorities, and get them to jointly engage with startups is something that we\'ve seen being very successful.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:22:33', '2016-11-15 17:22:33', '48444c78-374c-44d3-9fa1-0b989dbe6614'),
 ('362', '211', '5', '15', 'en_us', '6', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"15\",\"title\":\"How Do You Define Innovation?\",\"slug\":\"how-do-you-define-innovation\",\"postDate\":1477485180,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"210\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>&nbsp;Innovation is a bit of a messy word. We might feel that we intrinsically grasp its meaning, but how many of us can actually articulate what it means, especially as it relates to our specific business?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation has increasingly become a marketing buzzword, diluted by firms selling out of the box solutions to capitalize on what has become a blossoming hype curve.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>We wanted to know how to better support our partners in the future and avoid falling into the tropes of others. So, we conducted a survey of over 80 participants from the Rainmaking community that self-identified as working in the corporate innovation management space. The results are illuminating, and worth sharing. &nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Here<\\/strong><strong>\\u2019<\\/strong><strong>s a sample of what the community said about <\\/strong><strong>\\u201c<\\/strong><strong>innovation<\\/strong><strong>\\u201d<\\/strong><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/Picture11.png#asset:207:url\\\" alt=\\\"Picture11.png#asset:207\\\">It is easy to see how the word <em>innovation<\\/em> has become confused and abused. Responses ranged from bringing about sweeping visionary change all the way to solving a specific problem. There\\u2019s a lack of agreement on what the output of innovation should look like.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>At first glance, the responses can seem at odds. We think this is actually to be expected. Closer inspection shows there are consistent themes:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ol><li>There must be a positive change; something done, something created<\\/li><li>That change must be new; sometimes iterative, sometimes radical<\\/li><\\/ol>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Outcomes for innovation initiatives are defined based on their context in the specific market, industry or organization. It\\u2019s very specific to your circumstances. In summary, the most important definition of innovation is your own. <em>Innovation is<\\/em><em>&hellip;<\\/em><em>in the eye of the beholder.<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Here<\\/strong><strong>\\u2019<\\/strong><strong>s the current feeling about the <\\/strong><strong>\\u201c<\\/strong><strong>innovation industry<\\/strong><strong>\\u201d&nbsp;<\\/strong><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/Picture12.png#asset:209:url\\\" alt=\\\"Picture12.png#asset:209\\\">We loved the honesty!<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The industry that supports your initiatives can be noisy and fragmented. You\\u2019re fighting to deliver against short and long term objectives. Battling for attention with your core business. What you want is someone that is pragmatic in understanding your specific realities, not traditional strategies from self-proclaimed miracle workers.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>From the feedback we received,&nbsp;this quote really spoke to us:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<blockquote>We agree. When you combine this with the breadth of responses on why innovation is important\\u200a&mdash;\\u200afrom keeping the lights on, to delivering something tangible, to improving the world\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ait is clear that there can be a gap in getting from where you are today to where you\\u2019d like to be. The bridge that translates strategy into execution, talk into action.<\\/blockquote>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Start with the biggest risk<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/Screen-Shot-2016-10-26-at-11.32.37.png#asset:190:url\\\" alt=\\\"Screen-Shot-2016-10-26-at-11.32.37.png#a\\\" style=\\\"font-family:Arial, \'Helvetica Neue\', Helvetica, Tahoma, sans-serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:700;color:rgb(41,50,61);\\\"><\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>There are overlaps with these responses yet the top challenges are clear. Shifting mindsets, placing focus on change, and cultural adoption are the most glaringly consistent roadblocks in large organizations.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>While we create resources to support you with more thoughts, insights, tools and frameworks to overcome these challenges, here are a few interesting reads that will be helpful<\\/strong>:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/firstround.com\\/review\\/unlocking-the-benefits-of-self-management-without-going-all-in-on-holacracy\\/\\\">Unlocking the Benefits of Self-Management Without Going All In on Holacracy<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/firstround.com\\/review\\/unlocking-the-benefits-of-self-management-without-going-all-in-on-holacracy\\/\\\"><\\/a><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/medium.com\\/swlh\\/the-culture-deck-c4126ec63b18#.u3se1nxvm\\\">The Culture Deck: how people work is as important as what they do<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/medium.com\\/swlh\\/the-culture-deck-c4126ec63b18#.u3se1nxvm\\\"><\\/a><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/medium.com\\/the-corporate-startup\\/five-principles-for-building-corporate-innovation-ecosystems-3b421b7d70e5#.dmjl3qcag\\\">Five Principles for Building Corporate Innovation Ecosystems<\\/a>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/blog.strategyzer.com\\/posts\\/2016\\/6\\/20\\/why-companies-fail-how-to-prevent-it\\\">Why Companies Fail & How To Prevent It<\\/a>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/firstround.com\\/review\\/summer-book-recommendations-from-the-smartest-people-we-know\\/\\\">We also loved this curated list of Summer 2016 things to read from the amazing First Round<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/firstround.com\\/review\\/summer-book-recommendations-from-the-smartest-people-we-know\\/\\\"><\\/a>A few years old now, yet still relevant today:&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.100open.com\\/top-tips-for-building-an-innovation-culture\\/\\\">Top Tips for Building an Innovation Culture<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.100open.com\\/top-tips-for-building-an-innovation-culture\\/\\\"><\\/a><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=u6XAPnuFjJc\\\">Drive: The surprising truth about what motivates us<\\/a><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:24:21', '2016-11-15 17:24:21', '1b5cd9db-b859-4a67-8c0f-c9364470f352'),
 ('363', '184', '5', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"350\",\"title\":\"Bitcoin and Blockchain Investing: Interview with Meltem Demirors of DCG\",\"slug\":\"bitcoin-and-blockchain-investing-interview-with-meltem-demirors-of-dcg\",\"postDate\":1477477140,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"238\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Meltem Demirors, director of community at New York-based&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dcg.co\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Digital Currency Group (DCG)<\\/a>&nbsp;sits down with Startupbootcamp FinTech MD Jesse Podell to discuss the impact of blockchain, the changing nature of venture capital and the reasons she comes to work every morning.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/_roundPortrait\\/Picture1.png#asset:183:roundPortrait\\\" alt=\\\"Picture1.png#asset:183:roundPortrait\\\"><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Where do you see DCG\\u2019s fit in the bitcoin and blockchain ecosystem? Are you the 800 pound gorilla?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;We talked about this a lot when I first joined DCG \\u2013 Why do we come to work in the morning? What inspires us? What motivates us?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I think all of us fundamentally see bitcoin blockchain technology changing the financial system and the broader technology landscape.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>It doesn\\u2019t matter if we\\u2019re the 800 pound gorilla or the small upstart. I think for us we want to have an outsize impact and be an advocate, an evangelist, and the connector that helps make this industry more successful.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Do you see accelerators as a good idea for bitcoin and blockchain startups?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;&nbsp;Yes, absolutely.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>One thing I have noticed is that people who have gone through an accelerator program were much better at pitching, were much better at selling the value proposition, and were much better at creating a narrative. That skill set cannot be underestimated. You\\u2019re going through this rigorous program that\\u2019s designed to teach you all of these fantastic skills and competencies, and you\\u2019re learning from some of the best corporate VCs, the best corporate strategists, the best VCs, the best startup mentors that you normally wouldn\\u2019t have access to in your network. It\\u2019s a great way to compress that learning in a really short timeline and to really grow your network and also get great PR. No brainer for me.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Obviously, we\\u2019re super excited to have Startupbootcamp FinTech here and really excited about the startups that will go through your program.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse: &nbsp;What\\u2019s your general advice for startups who might be applying for an accelerator?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;I think people are always a little hesitant about applying. They think: \\u201cOh, it\\u2019s three months away from product development. That\\u2019s difficult. I want to focus on the tech.\\u201d No, no, no, no! Spend three months really getting good at sales, at communicating, at branding, at messaging, building relationships. That is going to do so much more for you&nbsp;than building a great product because growth takes two things. It takes a great product, but it also takes a great sales strategy. Remember that there\\u2019s more to the equation than just the technology and really focus on this opportunity to develop relationships and competencies that are going to help you grow beyond the seed stage.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;Where do you see the venture capital model heading in five years?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;I think a lot more people are excited about venture capital. A lot of people want to be investors. It\\u2019s like a sexy thing to do right now, which is great. I love it. The more money that goes into the ecosystem, the more ideas start getting thrown around.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What I think you\\u2019re seeing, though, is a decoupling of the size of the check that an investor\\u2019s able to write and the value that they\\u2019re able to add to an early stage company. We at DCG invest at the seed stage. We aim for 2% to 5% ownership, but we write smaller cheques.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What you\\u2019re going to start to see are two different types of investors. You\\u2019re going to see one investor who\\u2019s really focused on network effects, on connectivity, who\\u2019s really focused on value-added services, and another investor that\\u2019s really focused on late stage growth. They\\u2019re going to play two very different roles within the life cycle of a startup.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;What advice would you have for companies who want to pitch DCG?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp; For us, we\\u2019re seed stage investors. What our investing team looks at are three things. Number one, the team. Who are you? What\\u2019s your track record and what\\u2019s your story? Why are you starting this company? We need to see that you have grit and that you have determination and that you really care.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The second is product. Technically, what have you built? Open source software is notoriously competitive, so having teams that are technically competent is very important.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Then the last one is market. How do you think about monetization, and what\\u2019s the timeline on that? We\\u2019re different from most VCs in that we\\u2019re not a fund. We don\\u2019t have a certain timeline. If it\\u2019s going to take you 10 years to reach profitability, I think we\\u2019re okay with that, but you need to have a plan and then you need to have a backup plan and a backup plan to the backup plan.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Jesse:&nbsp;&nbsp;What about the role of Community Manager, how do you see it evolving?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Meltem:&nbsp;&nbsp;When I started my role was pretty specific. It was focused on developing better connective tissue between our companies. Now that we have a number of strategic investors on board we started to realize the value of having a broad network. For me, it\\u2019s about building the DCG brand, building relationships, and also creating new opportunities and new ways of thinking around how to internalize innovation within a large organization. &nbsp;It\\u2019s about taking the community role, untangling into the various components that really move the needle and making it more of a discipline.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To read the full interview, please click<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.linkedin.com\\/pulse\\/my-interview-meltem-demirors-dcg-jesse-podell?published=t\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">&nbsp;here<\\/a>:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Follow&nbsp;Meltem Demirors on <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/twitter.com\\/Melt_Dem\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Twitter<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/twitter.com\\/Melt_Dem\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"><\\/a>&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;\\u2013<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/dcg.co\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Digital Currency Group&nbsp;<\\/a>manages a large early stage investment portfolio in the digital currency and blockchain space. Recently they announced venture round with a number of leading financial institutions and venture capital firms including MasterCard, Bain Capital Ventures, New York Life and RRE Ventures. &nbsp;The firm had already established itself as a predominant investor of early stage bitcoin startups, with over 50 holdings currently in its portfolio.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:27:53', '2016-11-15 17:27:53', 'b427b654-3a2e-4adb-b49a-32f00d8f9711'),
 ('364', '149', '5', '15', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"351\",\"title\":\"The Future of Customer Acquisition is Already Here\",\"slug\":\"the-future-of-customer-acquisition-is-already-here\",\"postDate\":1477414080,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"148\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Chatbots are more than just the latest marketing gimmick \\u2013 they\\u2019re a clue to how the internet itself is likely to evolve. Insurers without a plan for some form of chatbot pilot risk losing out as online advertising undergoes its next big step change.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Chatbots are the hottest customer-centric innovative technology of 2016 so far. In March,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/2016\\/3\\/30\\/11332494\\/microsoft-bot-framework-build\\\">Microsoft<\\/a>&nbsp;announced the launch of a new platform that will enable anyone to build one. In April,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/techcrunch.com\\/2016\\/04\\/12\\/agents-on-messenger\\/\\\">Facebook<\\/a>&nbsp;announced the launch of chatbots on its existing Messenger platform.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What are chatbots? At the most basic level, these are computer programs that use artificial intelligence to simulate conversations with a real person.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>They have the obvious potential benefit of replacing customer service staff \\u2013 or freeing up those employees for other tasks, thus increasing productivity. But the marketing potential is even greater, as they enable companies to initiate conversations with customers online based on what sites they\\u2019re on and what kind of services they might be looking for.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Targeting new customers more effectively<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>In insurance, they could be used to replace the need to fill out long, tedious forms. Not only that, but since a chatbot can initiate a conversation, you can use them to proactively target prospective customers rather than wait for them to come to you. This is the vision behind Spixii, a startup we\\u2019ve been working with at InsurTech.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Spixii aims to make the buying of health and travel insurance more intuitive and fun for millennials, and to generate more revenues for insurers by opening up the relatively untapped millennial market \\u2013 and then upselling to these consumers in a more targeted and less pushy manner.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>With Spixii, the chatbot acts you\\u2019re having an online conversation with a human insurance agent, asking you questions and responding to your answers. The consumer gets a more engaging experience than just filling out a form, while the insurer can carry out an accurate risk assessment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Right now Spixii has several tier one insurers interested in partnering with them to run a pilot. They also have just been accepted on the Allianz Accelerator programme in France to test their offering further. Cynics may dismiss the technology as a gimmick. But no one can afford not to start experimenting with it, for one very simple reason: Facebook wants to supplant Google as the number one advertising platform on the internet, and they\\u2019re investing heavily in chatbots to help them do this.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Facebook is no longer a social media company \\u2013 here\\u2019s why that matters<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.vox.com\\/2016\\/5\\/10\\/11640140\\/facebook-media-influence\\\">Facebook<\\/a>&nbsp;is no longer a social network. It\\u2019s a technology holding company just like Google, and it now comprises social media, photo-sharing (Instagram), messaging (WhatsApp) and virtual reality (Oculus). It\\u2019s also the largest media distributor in history.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The company has grown with one goal: to make it so that no one who uses the internet ever has to leave the Facebook platform. Once we reach \\u201cPeak Facebook\\u201d \\u2013 the point at which the majority of the world\\u2019s internet users spend all their internet time on one or other of Facebook\\u2019s apps \\u2013 it will become pointless to advertise anywhere else.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>After all, Facebook already tales up 22% of the internet time that Americans spend on mobile devices, compared with 11% on Google search and YouTube combined. And Facebook\'s advertising revenues have more than doubled in the last two years, to <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.economist.com\\/news\\/briefing\\/21696507-social-network-has-turned-itself-one-worlds-most-influential-technology-giants\\\">$18 billion in 2015<\\/a>.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Chatbot failure is not an option<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>And why is Facebook so interested in chatbots? Because by creating its own advertising platform, it can control how people buy products and services online. Specifically, the company wants the whole transaction to take place within its own platform \\u2013 so customers never have to leave it. And hosting chatbots looks set to be one of the most effective ways of doing this.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Now, this trend towards internet dominance may or may not pay off. And it certainly throws up some questions about the fact that Facebook could end up with complete control \\u2013 or at least de facto dominance \\u2013 over how companies can advertise to their consumers online. But Facebook\\u2019s growth has been so phenomenal, and its increasing influence so unstoppable, that running some kind of chatbot pilot is not something insurers can afford to see as a luxury. It\\u2019s a necessity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>How insurers can exploit this trend<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The fastest way to trial your own chatbot is through partnerships and pilots \\u2013 either with technology companies themselves or with innovative startups who aim to solve a business problem that you\\u2019re struggling with.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To go back to the example of Spixii I mentioned before: this company represents an ideal opportunity for insurers to tap into the millennial market, and, in so doing, to investigate how the technology could be extended to reach other markets and develop attractive new propositions and products. Plus, it potentially offers a level of customer engagement and insight for small premium insurance products that just wouldn\\u2019t be affordable otherwise.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Facebook is serious about this technology. If successful, it could transform the world of online advertising beyond recognition. It may be that insurers can\\u2019t afford not to trial the technology, but those who are successful stand to reap huge potential rewards.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:32:27', '2016-11-15 17:32:27', 'f7863887-1d39-4fca-9666-85a2fa1f4df7'),
 ('365', '146', '5', '15', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"Missed Connections in the Sandbox\",\"slug\":\"missed-connections-in-the-sandbox\",\"postDate\":1477413360,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"145\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>This week, industry thought leaders from incumbent banks and FinTech startups gathered in the Rainmaking Loft for the first in the Autumn Season for the Rainmaking Sessions\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a<em>Playing in the sandbox<\\/em>. The session looked at the establishment of the Regulatory Sandbox run by the Financial Conduct Authority and the appetite and capability of many incumbent banks to participate in the new scheme and partner with new entrants to the financial services landscape.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The outcome? There are many footprints in the sandbox, but many may have to wait some time for impressive castles to be built.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA\\u2019s Regulatory Sandbox is meant to be a legal framework or a \\u2018safe space\\u2019 where businesses can test innovative products, services, business models and delivery mechanisms. This is a progressive step for startups in regulated industries, like financial services. However, many young companies still need active partnerships with established banks, firms and other corporates in order to test developing products with live data, enterprise architecture and an active customer base.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Sandboxes, like the one set up by the FCA in the UK, are a step in the right direction for regulated industries. But they struggle to be useful if certain startups aren\\u2019t given the resources to test their products, properly.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The FCA sandbox was designed to allow for collaboration. Currently, there are many FinTech startups involved in the programme. The FCA does not make public the names or the number of startups participating in the sandbox. However, many of these companies still require participation from incumbent banks in order to adequately test their offerings in the safe legal framework the FCA has established.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>However many banks, themselves, are working on creating their own innovation labs to not only support and welcome new technology and services entrants, but to enable and empower their own internal staff to embrace innovation. Many in this industry know that incumbent banks and financial services firms move at a pace considered much slower than is enjoyed in the Silicon Valley-style startup world. This is true even for banks that are working towards creating a more agile and flexible work environment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The window of opportunity is open now to work within the FCA Regulatory Sandbox. This time around the pace of change and collaboration may be more \\u2018missed connections\\u2019 than Match.com.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:36:56', '2016-11-15 17:36:56', '67fa197a-483e-4343-93fa-94e07d07318c'),
 ('366', '144', '5', '15', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"Shaping the Future of Banks and SMEs\",\"slug\":\"shaping-the-future-of-banks-and-smes\",\"postDate\":1477413240,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"143\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<p>Peers from a wide range of UK and European banks, along with a couple of FinTech startups, arrived at the Rainmaking Loft for the last in the Summer Season for the Rainmaking Sessions. As the group munched on bacon rolls and sipped tea and coffee, all were in the room with the understanding that small to medium sized businesses are a group that is under loved, underserved and ripe with opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The roundtable discussion, led by Justin Hannemann, Head of Product Experience (Customer and Innovation), Santander UK and Johanna Pugh, global head of Lending, Misys caused several themes to emerge from the table.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>SMEs are quite diverse and can range from everything from a tech-savvy FinTech startup in London to a cat grooming store in Sheffield, for example. This makes SMEs hard to classify and are seen as risky and complex by banks. Categorisation is hard when <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/blog.thecompanywarehouse.co.uk\\/2012\\/07\\/31\\/what-is-an-sme\\/\\\">definitions differ<\\/a> between UK government departments, HMRC and even the EU. As banks enhance their services to retail customers and larger commercial organisations, SMEs get pushed to the bottom.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Internal bank politics as well as legacy systems don\\u2019t make it easier for traditional firms to develop services that meets the needs of most SMEs. Many banks make due with an enhanced retail bank offering or a \\u2018lite\\u2019 version of their corporate offerings\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aboth versions tend to fall short of meeting SME needs. Legacy systems inside banks can also make it difficult to shift customer accounts from one product set to another if an SME is initially put in the \\u2018retail portfolio\\u2019 at the bank.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Despite much discussion around open APIs and working with FinTech startups, many banks around the table favoured a more human approach to better meet SME needs. Bringing customers into the bank, even giving some of them a seat on the board, was seen as the main tool to better understand SME needs and break down internal barriers at the bank. \\u201cThey are the boss,\\u201d was one comment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>SME pain points can be huge. They are working 24\\/7 to keep their business running, but many lack basic accounting skills or are uneasy about chasing unpaid invoices. SMEs are looking for control and simplification, according to the roundtable. SMEs want to be able to make deposits, get invoices paid and not have to deal with complex or confusing financial products.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Digital did not reign supreme with SME needs either. Many SMEs are looking for access to human-led customer service where they could pick up the phone and speak to an expert at any time. \\u201cWhen you are dealing with amounts over six figures, people want a personal chat, not 100% digital\\u201d, was one roundtable comment.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Globally, the majority of businesses can be classified as small businesses. The future of SMEs is central to the future of FinTech and corporate banking. Empowering SMEs and helping them shape their future is a huge opportunity.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To find out more about Rainmaking Innovation follow us on @rainmakinginnov or visit us at <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/rainmaking.io\\/\\\">https:\\/\\/rainmaking.io\\/<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/rainmaking.io\\/\\\"><\\/a>To find out more about Misys visit <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.misys.com\\/solutions\\/fusionbanking\\/lending\\/\\\">http:\\/\\/www.misys.com\\/solutions\\/fusionbanking\\/lending\\/<\\/a><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:37:10', '2016-11-15 17:37:10', 'e804639c-a5dd-43d8-9adc-a90025bc583d'),
 ('367', '136', '5', '15', 'en_us', '7', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"What Do You Want Your Bank To Solve?\",\"slug\":\"what-do-you-want-your-bank-to-solve\",\"postDate\":1477412460,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"128\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<h2>Problematic Personas&nbsp;<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A couple of years ago, I attended a Bank Innovation afternoon, run by the lovely JP Nichols, where I encountered my first \\u2018persona\\u2019 exercise. The room was full of design people, FinTech folks and bankers. My group were the bankers.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>We were assigned to create a person. A real-life person, with wants and desires, flaws and problems\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aand then create a banking relationship for that \\u2018person\\u2019. I was amazed by the variety of different people created by each group.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A group of designers created an old age pensioner, who lived in a rural community and was a widower. Some consultants outlined a single mother of two, who lived in the Northeast in the UK, and was going back to school to continue her education. Yet another group constructed a former addict in London, who had served in Iraq.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My group, the bankers? This was our guy:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ol><li>A man (I think we ended up calling him Trevor)<\\/li><li>28 years old. University and above education.<\\/li><li>Works for a large corporate, but wants to start his own business eventually.<\\/li><li>Small pension plan established.<\\/li><li>Owns his own home&nbsp;&hellip; in <em>London.<\\/em> &lt;==WTF?<\\/li><li><\\/li><\\/ol>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I had to stop them. (They were all getting collective hard-ons about the type of small business loans their bank would sell to this future Steve Jobs of the UK.) I had to ask\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a\\u2018<em>Does this perfect human being have any flaws? Any problems?\\u2019<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>They stared at me blankly.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u2018<em>Ok, guys\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ais he married, does he have a girlfriend<\\/em>?\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>No&nbsp;girlfriend as of yet\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abut definitely wants to get married some day<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I wrote\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a\\u2018<em>Uses Tinder\\u2019<\\/em> on a Post-It<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Really, online dating? Would our guy do that?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u2018<em>YES!<\\/em>\\u2019 I screamed. (The room got a bit quiet then) \\u2018<em>Your perfect, 28 year old Oxbridge grad, with an endless disposable income\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agiven that he has a pension AND owns his own home in London\\u200a&mdash;\\u200acannot actually magic up the perfect trophy wife at will. He uses Tinder just like all the rest of you<\\/em>.\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The group started discussing what type of cool, hip tech startup this guy would start before his 30th birthday.\\u2018<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Gentlemen!<\\/em> (I can get loud when I\\u2019m not being heard&nbsp;;-) ) <em>Focus\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abefore you start selling \\u2018Trevor\\u2019 a wide range of banking products, we have to discuss his flaws, his quirks\\u200a&mdash;\\u200athe stuff that makes him a real human being. Does he have a gambling problem, for example?\\u2019<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>At that point one of the men in the group took my pink Post-It pad and Sharpie and wrote \\u2018Buys scratch cards\\u2019 on a sheet and triumphantly stuck it on the flip board.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Person&nbsp;Before&nbsp;Product<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Why am I telling you this story?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This week I was asked to think about some stories that addressed customer facing problems that banks can try and solve. My brain went into action. Account opening! KYC! Identity!<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I was no different from those \\u2018bankers\\u2019 two years ago. I started thinking about bank products\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agranted I was thinking about how these bank products aren\\u2019t fit for many individual people\\u2019s purposes\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abut I was being product-centric nevertheless.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I decided to walk through my life.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li>I want a way that I can get from my house in the morning to my desk in my office in the cheapest and most efficient way possible. &lt;==<em>Southeastern Rail is not delivering<\\/em><\\/li><li>I want&nbsp;to be able to get a taxi anytime and anywhere, without going to an ATM first &lt;==<em>Oh ya, Uber solved tha<\\/em><\\/li><li>I want to be able to walk around a conference centre, in my dress with no pockets, and still hold onto\\u200a&mdash;\\u200amy bank card, my phone, a lipstick and a tampon\\u200a&mdash;\\u200awithout carrying a huge bag &lt;==<em>My \\u2018tiny, pretty, purse\\u2019 startup company is looking for funds now<\\/em><\\/li><li>I want a summer house at the bottom of my garden.<\\/li><li>I want my son to have guitar lessons<\\/li><li>I want to know I can buy a ticket to the US at a moment notice if my family needs me<\\/li><li>I want to be able to work at something until I have more grey hair than I have now<\\/li><li>I want my son to go to university where the only thing he has to worry about is studying and having enough weekly beer money\\u200a&mdash;\\u200alike I did.<\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Can a bank look at all of that and think\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aWhat are the services we have now that can help you achieve some of that and if not, what can we develop that can?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Or would they try and sell me a \\u2018loan\\u2019?<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:37:28', '2016-11-15 17:37:28', 'a9e523ca-7a16-44db-91a2-c5ec7ea014cc'),
 ('368', '126', '5', '15', 'en_us', '8', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"Customer Service and the \\\"Little Pockets of Data\\\"\",\"slug\":\"customer-service-and-the-little-pockets-of-data\",\"postDate\":1477411620,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"125\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<h2>\\\"There is Only One Channel- The Customer Channel<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A few years ago Don Callahan, Head of Operations & Technology at Citi gave a talk at the bank\\u2019s annual Digital Money Symposium in London. He decided to conduct an experiment. He sat down with his family to try and construct a central view of all of their household finances, both incoming and outgoing. All the paycheques, credit cards, pension plans, investments, mortgages, loans etc&hellip;for everyone. And he couldn\\u2019t do it. The struggles his own household were having was reflected in most banks inability to produce a comprehensive, centralised view of their customers.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>I have spent the past few years writing about the challenges banks face when looking to connect better with their customers. I have hammered home the idea that there is only one channel\\u200a&mdash;\\u200athe customer channel. But I have never looked at myself, to illustrate this, with a personal story.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Missed&nbsp;connections<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My family is a strange beast. Our relationship with providers of financial services is almost, exclusively centred on one bank. We have our joint account, our mortgage, our credit cards, ISAs, pensions, savings accounts\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aall with the same institution. That should mean if any bank has a clear, helicopter view of my family\\u2019s financial situation\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aor even recognize who I am\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ait should be my bank.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>You\\u2019d think.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Recently, we decided to redo our mortgage to get a better rate\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aon the advice of our relationship manager. (We\\u2019ll call him \\u2018Alan\\u2019 for the sake of this story). When we sent in the forms, the bank came back to my husband to say \\u2018Wait, your wife (who is named on your joint account) doesn\\u2019t live at the address where we were doing the remortgage.\\u2019<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What, wait, what?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Let\\u2019s back up a bit.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>My family\\u200a&mdash;\\u200awhich is myself, my husband and our son (and at the time a hamster\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aRIP \\u2018Kevin\\u2019) \\u2013moved to a new house in 2013. It\\u2019s a lovely house, with a double layer garden, big kitchen, on a dead end street, detached\\u200a&mdash;\\u200abut those aren\\u2019t the details you, the reader, should be concerned with now.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Anyone who has moved house knows the joys of \\u2018changing your addresses at every credit card, loyalty points scheme, electoral register etc&hellip;One of the first addresses we changed was on our joint account. Actually, the first address we changed, was on our mortgage papers, which has both my husband\\u2019s and my name on it. Then we changed our joint account. Which is where our standing order for our mortgage is paid out from.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>We had two blissful years of living in our lovely, London suburbs house, paying our mortgage out of our joint account. Paper documents, listing these accounts, were posted to our domestic idyll.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Then we tried to remortgage. We found out, that according to our bank\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aI still lived at the little Victoria terraced house, on a street in southeast London\\u200a&mdash;\\u200awhere we have lived two years prior.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Mind you\\u200a&mdash;\\u200amy credit card travelled to the new house (it has five bedrooms and a grannie flat\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ayou really must drop by when you are in town) My savings account, travelled to the new house. My Sainsbury\\u2019s Nectar points card\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aswitched address. But only my husband\\u2019s side of the *joint-account* travelled a few miles, to the outskirts of London, to the Kent borders.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Why? Because it was only my husband, who changed the address.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>To quote our relationship manager\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a\\u201cWe do not *assume* that that both names on a joint account live at the same&nbsp;address.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>:-|<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Please do not argue with me about bank procedure and KYC and regulations\\u200a&mdash;\\u200alike you work at a bank. Think, for a second, like a customer.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Two years after moving. Two years after dealing with my bank from the same address. Two years\\u2019 worth of \\u2018customer transaction data\\u2019 (yes, I know <em>banks<\\/em> can\\u2019t really use that!) Two years after *signing* the mortgage papers in a branch of the bank! 18 years of being a customer of this bank. I had to travel to a branch to produce documentation to prove who I was and where I lived.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>*That* is stupid.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Losing the Customer Experience Battle<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>That is why banks are losing the customer experience battle. Right there. Ground zero. The Lumley Household. Kent, UK.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The problem lies not in banks refusing to fix the customer experience problem. It lies in the current structure of regulations, legacy infrastructure and culture at banks that make it almost impossible to change the desire to be \\u2018customer-centric\\u2019 into an actual working practice.All of the products that my family holds with our bank\\u200a&mdash;\\u200afrom the current accounts, credit cards, mortgage etc..\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aall of those products are held in separate, distinct databases. Universal banks do not emerge fully formed from the head of the banking gods. They are constructed over time, through waves of acquisitions, and infrastructure products focused on product segments. These projects are built by IT teams that are often seconded in from outside firms (like IBM or Accenture) to work for 18 to 24 months at a time (depending on the project) and, more often than not, have very little direct knowledge of the business.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The customer story inside a bank is not held in a book or a central database. It is held in \\u2018little pockets of data\\u2019 spread all around the bank, in various locations, in an assortment of programming languages and platforms and architecture. These \\u2018little pockets of data\\u2019 never interact, are never reconciled, redundancies are never discovered\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aand most importantly\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aopportunities are never explored.<\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:37:52', '2016-11-15 17:37:52', '84dc5b95-1836-4286-b6cb-2bb2d14120dd'),
 ('369', '142', '5', '15', 'en_us', '8', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"The Key To Fostering Corporate Innovation Culture? Inside Out!\",\"slug\":\"the-key-to-fostering-corporate-innovation-culture-inside-out\",\"postDate\":1464971460,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"141\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<h2>How to Foster An Innovation Culture<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Many large firms are currently grappling with ways to incorporate a more innovative culture into their development and organisational environments. As with any large transformational project, success or failure tend to depend on the right mix of culture and human relationships.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This was the main crux of the discussion at the inaugural Rainmaking Session\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aHow to foster a corporate innovation culture\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ahosted by Rainmaking Innovation in May.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>A wide range of corporate innovation leaders and learners from organisations as diverse as Standard & Poors, BP and SwissRe gathered to hear a discussion led by Rachael Jackson, Solutions, Design, Services at RBS and Alex Farcet, partner at Rainmaking Innovation.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The conversation around the table, conducted under the Chatham House Rule, came thick and fast as participants&nbsp;relayed stories of their own companies\\u2019 internal challenges, strategies and successes. The only interruption to the discussion came when two enormous anti-terrorist transformer helicopters buzzed over&nbsp;the Rainmaking Loft!<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/Picture1_161031_172030.png#asset:309:url\\\" alt=\\\"Picture1_161031_172030.png#asset:309\\\"><br><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Our Findings<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>The main findings from the roundtable were as follows:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation leaders at corporations need to operate with one leg inside an organisation and one leg outside. Being outside a firm allows the leaders to learn and discover new technologies and new business models that can transform the enterprise. While keeping a foot inside a company, keeps lines of communication and collaboration open with senior people at the firm.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This line of talk moved onto a debate on whether innovation departments need to be centralised, and separate from the main organisation, with their own staff, budget and authority, or decentralised. The centralised model had the advantages of a separate budget line which would allow projects to develop without relying on the P&L of separate business units. The decentralised approach emphasised the importance of encouraging the entire firm to engage in innovation projects and activities.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation tends to signal change for most companies and change is scary. People and culture are key to ensuring that establishing an&nbsp;innovation culture is seen as beneficial and empowering to the rest of the organisation.<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/1KuyS3TbSOtuUIL3loV17JA.png#asset:140:url\\\" alt=\\\"1KuyS3TbSOtuUIL3loV17JA.png#asset:140\\\"><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Many around the Rainmaking Session breakfast table recognised that a large number of&nbsp;innovation projects were led by either senior management or staff working hands on in development. It was the so-called \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 that was most in need of empowerment when it came to innovation. A large proportion of the group argued that this \\u2018middle layer\\u2019 was not incentivised to try anything new or to embark on innovation projects that have the possibility of failure embedded in their DNA.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Innovation projects are hard to measure, and including metrics at all might be detrimental to its successes. However, most large corporates operate in a risk culture that requires performance metrics and measurement. The \\u2018can\\u2019t live with metrics\\/can\\u2019t live without metrics\\u2019 debate continues.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Advice to Startups<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Finally, the roundtable debate focused engaging with and working with startups. The large corporate around the table all expressed an interest and a desire to work with startups\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agiven that the search for new technologies and solutions is often found in the startup community.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Their advice for any startup looking to sell into or partner with a larger organisation was to make sure that they presented their value proposition in a way that made sense for the corporate and their clients\\u2019 needs. If that value proposition was met correctly, a partnership between a corporate and a startup would be more likely to be successful. These successful projects could then be used as evidence to the rest of the company that embarking on an innovation culture was beneficial and worthwhile.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>Please join us, or invite a colleague, for our next Rainmaking Session on June 16th\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aWhat\\u2019s the matter with payments?<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em>You will hear from:<\\/em>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul><li><em>Jon Prideaux, CEO at Boku<\\/em><\\/li><li><em>Richard Jackson, UK Managing Director, WoraPay<\\/em><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><em><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.eventbrite.co.uk\\/e\\/the-rainmaking-sessions-whats-the-matter-with-payments-tickets-25602215917\\\">Learn more here<\\/a><\\/em><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:38:43', '2016-11-15 17:38:43', '7eb269ad-cab8-4d9e-96a3-fe732113db17'),
 ('370', '139', '5', '15', 'en_us', '12', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"352\",\"title\":\"Women Are More Fun :)\",\"slug\":\"women-are-more-fun\",\"postDate\":1461860700,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"16\":[\"15\"],\"18\":[\"302\"],\"17\":[\"longForm\"],\"19\":\"\",\"15\":\"<h2>Bringing the Party to FinTech<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Women are more fun\\u200a&mdash;\\u200agame over&nbsp;:-)<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>After almost 22 years in this financial technology business, I have been to my fair share of events and dinners and meetups. I have sat through an hour long lecture on the problems inherent in the Payments Services Directive in Luxembourg. I\\u2019ve seen people slam their fists on a table in protest to the idea that social sign-in for bank accounts could be workable. I once belonged to the MiFID working group.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>But I have never ended an evening of discussion and chat in the FinTech space where several people left with comments such as:<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\u201cThis was the best meetup I have ever been too.\\u201d and (my favourite) \\u201cThis was better than the party I went to on Saturday night.\\u201d<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/0ouWnuc6GSOnllss2.jpg#asset:137:url\\\" alt=\\\"0ouWnuc6GSOnllss2.jpg#asset:137\\\"><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This was last night and the occasion was the second FemTech meetup, run by the formidable Ghela Boscovich of Zafin Labs and hosted by Lloyds Banking Group. The FemTech meetups were born out of a Swift Innotribe project for Sibos last year, and enabled by Sam Maule of Carlisle Consulting, to showcase and promote the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.femtechleaders.com\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">various women who work in global financial technology.<\\/a><\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.femtechleaders.com\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\"><\\/a>The numbers are appalling. <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.cityam.com\\/236156\\/women-in-fintech-four-ways-to-close-the-gender-gap-\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Less than five percent of startup founders<\\/a> in the FinTech space are women. Financial News published their annual <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.efinancialnews.com\\/gallery\\/financial-news-women-finance-survey\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Women in Finance<\\/a>&nbsp;survey\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aand the results show a mostly discouraged and, almost, depressed female workforce.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>What tends to get me angry (and I am trying not to write blogs angry anymore\\u200a&mdash;\\u200ahowever, passion is my muse!) is that whenever anyone in this industry talks about diversity, the burden of proof tends to fall on the people advocating diversity rather than those who sit idly by accepting the status quo.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>When just advocating the need for more women (just women, mind you!\\u200a&mdash;\\u200a50 percent of the population!) to participate in the FinTech space, statistics need to be rolled out highlighting how female led business tend to be more profitable or showing that adding women to their boards adds to a company\\u2019s longevity. Debates around systematic basis within financial services and tech, the glass ceiling and whether or not women know how to adequately \\u2018lean in\\u2019 (or whether they even need to) are starting to grate on my last nerve.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>So, in an effort to cultivate this attitude of focusing in the positive, I am going to throw out a brand new, entirely unscientific theory about why there needs to be more women in the FinTech space and why your company needs to hire more women now.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>Why You Need To Hire More Women- Now<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Women are more fun.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>There, I said it. Women make work more pleasant. They laugh, they are supportive. I don\\u2019t know many women who would sit and lecture for an hour on the PSD, in a stuffy room, in a grey suit. But I know many who would chat about the ramifications of the PSD 2, while wearing statement jewellery and sipping a glass of wine. Which room would you rather sit in?<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>There it is\\u200a&mdash;\\u200amy positive vibes for this week. Women make work and life and Tuesday night meetups talking about digital banking with Lloyds\\u2019 John Webster\\u200a&mdash;\\u200aa lot more fun. Pass me a glass of wine.<img src=\\\"http:\\/\\/s3.amazonaws.com\\/rainmaking\\/websiteImages\\/0ckJlJdo2-DFSJPuF.jpeg#asset:138:url\\\" alt=\\\"0ckJlJdo2-DFSJPuF.jpeg#asset:138\\\"><\\/p>\"}}', '2016-11-15 17:39:00', '2016-11-15 17:39:00', '4ea4b593-2c75-41f5-ba9c-9db97539b1b6'),
