 ('144', 'field', '15', 'en_us', ' peers from a wide range of uk and european banks along with a couple of fintech startups arrived at the rainmaking loft for the last in the summer season for the rainmaking sessions as the group munched on bacon rolls and sipped tea and coffee all were in the room with the understanding that small to medium sized businesses are a group that is under loved underserved and ripe with opportunity the roundtable discussion led by justin hannemann head of product experience customer and innovation santander uk and johanna pugh global head of lending misys caused several themes to emerge from the table smes are quite diverse and can range from everything from a tech savvy fintech startup in london to a cat grooming store in sheffield for example this makes smes hard to classify and are seen as risky and complex by banks categorisation is hard when definitions differ between uk government departments hmrc and even the eu as banks enhance their services to retail customers and larger commercial organisations smes get pushed to the bottom internal bank politics as well as legacy systems don t make it easier for traditional firms to develop services that meets the needs of most smes many banks make due with an enhanced retail bank offering or a lite version of their corporate offerings both versions tend to fall short of meeting sme needs legacy systems inside banks can also make it difficult to shift customer accounts from one product set to another if an sme is initially put in the retail portfolio at the bank despite much discussion around open apis and working with fintech startups many banks around the table favoured a more human approach to better meet sme needs bringing customers into the bank even giving some of them a seat on the board was seen as the main tool to better understand sme needs and break down internal barriers at the bank they are the boss was one comment sme pain points can be huge they are working 24 7 to keep their business running but many lack basic accounting skills or are uneasy about chasing unpaid invoices smes are looking for control and simplification according to the roundtable smes want to be able to make deposits get invoices paid and not have to deal with complex or confusing financial products digital did not reign supreme with sme needs either many smes are looking for access to human led customer service where they could pick up the phone and speak to an expert at any time when you are dealing with amounts over six figures people want a personal chat not 100% digital was one roundtable comment globally the majority of businesses can be classified as small businesses the future of smes is central to the future of fintech and corporate banking empowering smes and helping them shape their future is a huge opportunity to find out more about rainmaking innovation follow us on rainmakinginnov or visit us at https rainmaking io to find out more about misys visit http www misys com solutions fusionbanking lending '),
