 ('149', 'field', '15', 'en_us', ' chatbots are more than just the latest marketing gimmick they re a clue to how the internet itself is likely to evolve insurers without a plan for some form of chatbot pilot risk losing out as online advertising undergoes its next big step change chatbots are the hottest customer centric innovative technology of 2016 so far in march microsoft announced the launch of a new platform that will enable anyone to build one in april facebook announced the launch of chatbots on its existing messenger platform what are chatbots at the most basic level these are computer programs that use artificial intelligence to simulate conversations with a real person they have the obvious potential benefit of replacing customer service staff or freeing up those employees for other tasks thus increasing productivity but the marketing potential is even greater as they enable companies to initiate conversations with customers online based on what sites they re on and what kind of services they might be looking for targeting new customers more effectively in insurance they could be used to replace the need to fill out long tedious forms not only that but since a chatbot can initiate a conversation you can use them to proactively target prospective customers rather than wait for them to come to you this is the vision behind spixii a startup we ve been working with at insurtech spixii aims to make the buying of health and travel insurance more intuitive and fun for millennials and to generate more revenues for insurers by opening up the relatively untapped millennial market and then upselling to these consumers in a more targeted and less pushy manner with spixii the chatbot acts you re having an online conversation with a human insurance agent asking you questions and responding to your answers the consumer gets a more engaging experience than just filling out a form while the insurer can carry out an accurate risk assessment right now spixii has several tier one insurers interested in partnering with them to run a pilot they also have just been accepted on the allianz accelerator programme in france to test their offering further cynics may dismiss the technology as a gimmick but no one can afford not to start experimenting with it for one very simple reason facebook wants to supplant google as the number one advertising platform on the internet and they re investing heavily in chatbots to help them do this facebook is no longer a social media company here s why that matters facebook is no longer a social network it s a technology holding company just like google and it now comprises social media photo sharing instagram messaging whatsapp and virtual reality oculus it s also the largest media distributor in history the company has grown with one goal to make it so that no one who uses the internet ever has to leave the facebook platform once we reach peak facebook the point at which the majority of the world s internet users spend all their internet time on one or other of facebook s apps it will become pointless to advertise anywhere else after all facebook already tales up 22% of the internet time that americans spend on mobile devices compared with 11% on google search and youtube combined and facebook s advertising revenues have more than doubled in the last two years to $18 billion in 2015 chatbot failure is not an option and why is facebook so interested in chatbots because by creating its own advertising platform it can control how people buy products and services online specifically the company wants the whole transaction to take place within its own platform so customers never have to leave it and hosting chatbots looks set to be one of the most effective ways of doing this now this trend towards internet dominance may or may not pay off and it certainly throws up some questions about the fact that facebook could end up with complete control or at least de facto dominance over how companies can advertise to their consumers online but facebook s growth has been so phenomenal and its increasing influence so unstoppable that running some kind of chatbot pilot is not something insurers can afford to see as a luxury it s a necessity how insurers can exploit this trend the fastest way to trial your own chatbot is through partnerships and pilots either with technology companies themselves or with innovative startups who aim to solve a business problem that you re struggling with to go back to the example of spixii i mentioned before this company represents an ideal opportunity for insurers to tap into the millennial market and in so doing to investigate how the technology could be extended to reach other markets and develop attractive new propositions and products plus it potentially offers a level of customer engagement and insight for small premium insurance products that just wouldn t be affordable otherwise facebook is serious about this technology if successful it could transform the world of online advertising beyond recognition it may be that insurers can t afford not to trial the technology but those who are successful stand to reap huge potential rewards '),
