 ('242', 'field', '15', 'en_us', ' car2go uber and apps like ally are just three examples of such services that are changing the way we get from a to b that is not to say that car ownership is no longer significant indeed 73% of households in berlin still own at least one car needless to say if the shift from car ownership to mobility services is inevitable we still have a long way to go there are however trends that are spurring on this shift we ll take a closer look at three of them smartphone adoption urbanization and access over ownership in germany the use of mobile devices to access the internet on the go is on the rise according to data from emarketer in 2015 54% of residents used their smartphone to access the internet in comparison to 40% in 2013 in addition 28% of berlin residents use travel apps with their smartphones daily while another 22% use travel apps one to three times a week the further adoption of smartphones will likely lead to an increase in the use of new mobility services and provide an opportunity for businesses and other stakeholders to use this platform to create new technology urbanization urbanization is a global megatrend over 75% of the population of germany lives in cities and it is estimated that by 2030 60% of the world s population will live in cities combine this with the trend that people are spending more time in transit and it becomes clear that municipal governments have a major challenge on their hands their job will be to improve quality of life in denser cities due to this charging urban environment car ownership will become increasingly difficult to support the risks ranging from worsening air pollution to traffic congestion are incredibly high if municipal governments aren t open to and supportive of mobility options outside of what we are already accustomed to in addition to changes in public policy we will also likely see city residents taking initiative and altering their mobility habits as a result of the changes to urban life this topic of evolving habits in consumer culture leads us to our final trend access over ownership according to researcher rachel botsman people are wired to share in her book what s mine is yours the rise of collaborative consumption she explains that we as consumers are currently experiencing a significant shift in values and that we are putting aside our desire for ownership to instead reconnect with products in a more meaningful way a report by price waterhouse coopers supports her claim and states the sharing economy is growing as consumers choose access over ownership does that mean that car ownership will eventually be a thing of the past the trends smartphone adoption urbanization and access over ownership will certainly play their part but the future of mobility will also be determined by new technology techcrunch journalist george arison wrote and anyone who has ever tried to strap a car seat in the back of an uber can tell you there is nothing quite like owning your own car especially when you become a parent uber revolutionized transportation but the service today isn t a silver bullet the market is still wide open for hungry corporations and startups to make their mark with new innovative solutions and you can be sure we ll be watching the latest developments very closely '),
